commit_message:
Really ensure that sphinx <1.2 is installed

Because sphinx have release on pypi version suffixed by a letter for beta
purpose, ie: 1.2b3, even <1.2 is in requirement.txt 1.2b3 is installed.

This changes force the upper version to 1.1.999, to not install beta version
of sphinx 1.2.

Change-Id: I951951ce24388cc1c7a9e472daf58a1e12124aba
Closes-bug: #1346827

commit_message:
swift: remove compression

This was necessary back when using the first driver version using
Whisper instead of Carbonara, but this is not needed anymore and will
reduce latency.

Change-Id: I8ae7a27298636ca9e0504a316c48d8f2c930565f

commit_message:
Explicitly states the keystonemiddleware version

Currently, there is no version listed. However, there exists a page for
version 0 of the library in pypi.

https://pypi.python.org/pypi/keystonemiddleware/0

This change states the version of the library to "greater than equal"
1.0.0 which is the first real version of the same.

Change-Id: I2bbee6db56e166387d34a4655996a85db9b64ad3

Set top version for python-keystoneclient

Required to ensure that no system level dependencies will be
added to keystoneclient, which can break our ci

Hi Julien,

I haven't been able to find the source of the error as yet, but it seems like the new aggregation logic when combined with the serialization-deserialization loop, limits the values stored to at most the last two values received in the case of datapoints (1.0, 2.0, .., 10.0) POSTed individually for timestamps within subsequent seconds.

Here are the values I'm seeing serialized on each cycle:

  http://paste.openstack.org/show/85614/

As a result, when the aggregations are retrieved, IINM the aggregate values are all equal the last.

All except std, which I see always returned as null ... I suspect that some special-casing around len(ts)==1 is required for the std aggregate, as stddev is undefined for a single datapoint.

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2014-07-08 14:46:07.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

Thanks Eoghan, that debugging is helpful.

So the problem is that the BoundTimeSpan in the archive should be 2*block_size so the aggregation is working correctly. I knew it but I mistyped. ;-) I just fixed that, let me know how that goes.

Not sure what's wrong with std, I'll give it a try locally, maybe it need to be a special case."}, {'account_id': 1669, 'date': '2014-07-08 14:46:26.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-08 14:46:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
carbonara: change time serie aggregation implementation

Following recent discussions, this uses a new scheme to implement the
timeserie aggregation in Carbonara.
We use a infinite-precision timeserie in TimeSerieArchive that is used
to compute the aggregation of all the archived timeseries.

Change-Id: I346ba5b316049ba622c8f6e633cf9aaea1c0519c

commit_message:
Initial cirros element

Creates a cirros image ready to be booted in openstack.
It can receive a specific cirros version via DIB_CIRRROS_RELEASE
environment variable, accepting also the value 'latest' for newest
release.

Change-Id: Ic6baa3366b6d148829e0b6f9c6d2e411fdde4072

[{'created': '2014-03-24 15:31:55.000000000', 'message': "Hardcode the logging level in swift_middleware

Now Swift writes it's proxy-server-logs into syslog as well as swift-proxy.log.
This behaviour is to be changed after adding oslo.logging into Swift.
From the other hand, we use pipeline.setup_pipeline inside Swift. And all swift-logging configs
become applied to Ceilometer's pipeline. As a result (in case of DEBUG is on) we see too many
Ceilometr-related messages in syslog.

This fix partially closes the bug below.

Closes bug 1294789

Change-Id: Ibec7ef8ca763e577235077a086f002f9683d5296
"}]
commit_message:
Hardcode the logging level in swift_middleware

Now Swift writes it's proxy-server-logs into syslog as well as swift-proxy.log.
This behaviour is to be changed after adding oslo.logging into Swift.
From the other hand, we use pipeline.setup_pipeline inside Swift. And all swift-logging configs
become applied to Ceilometer's pipeline. As a result (in case of DEBUG is on) we see too many
Ceilometr-related messages in syslog.

This fix partially closes the bug below.

Closes bug 1294789

Change-Id: Ibec7ef8ca763e577235077a086f002f9683d5296

commit_message:
Allow capabilities to be set on ironic nodes

Since Ide39f4a2796b169025bf0083e021166ae35f30f8, Ironic has been able to
pass nodes' capabilities to the nova scheduler to allow for more
flexible and precise scheduling of instances.  This patch allows devtest
to pass capabilities from nodes.json (if they are present) to the
'ironic node-update' command which is already used to set nodes'
cpu_arch, memory and disk.

Part of bp targeted-node-deployment

Change-Id: I533336d193ee7bc46a7be79ff689f447aaf5770a

commit_message:
Add drivers.base.BaseDriver.get_properties()

Adds ironic.drivers.base.BaseDriver.get_properties() which returns a
dictionary of <property>:<description> entries.

The driver interfaces (DeployInterface, PowerInterface, ...) have a
new get_properties() method that returns a dictionary of
<property>:<description>.

These changes are needed in order to provide an API to get driver_info
properties.

Change-Id: I5994e990deb26841633ca26de1a5fb63b743271a
Blueprint: get-required-driver-info
Partial-Bug: #1261915

commit_message:
Set glance control_exchange to 'glance'

Glance control_exchange in glance-api.conf wasn't set
and glance used default value for this - 'openstack'.
So, exchange 'glance' and queue 'glance' didn't exist in rabbit.
But ceilometer as default glance control exchange uses 'glance'.
This patch fixes the fix for this problem and change-id as well

Closes-bug: #1335891

Change-Id: Idd1566dd507878b2f01c2d0ff9956dedc77a4461
Signed-off-by: Bogdan Dobrelya <bdobrelia@mirantis.com>

[{'created': '2014-07-18 14:10:46.000000000', 'message': 'Fix for unneccessary resampling of single-value timeseries

Resampling a timeseries with one element is unnecessary,
and causes problems in the case of an aggregated timeseries
with aggregation method set to stddev, as the single already-
aggregated value is then discarded due to standard deviation
being undefined for a single datapoint.

The new test fails with the original unselective resampling.

Change-Id: I7f0db8050c0cef5eceec24977e4cb02d4843824d
'}]
commit_message:
Fix for unneccessary resampling of single-value timeseries

Resampling a timeseries with one element is unnecessary,
and causes problems in the case of an aggregated timeseries
with aggregation method set to stddev, as the single already-
aggregated value is then discarded due to standard deviation
being undefined for a single datapoint.

The new test fails with the original unselective resampling.

Change-Id: I7f0db8050c0cef5eceec24977e4cb02d4843824d

commit_message:
Validate available services regions

This introduces middleware that is used to validate the
available services regions. It makes sure that the initial
region has a compute service and is reachable. If a region
does not provide a compute service endpoint it will be
removed from the list of available regions. If there are no
regions with a compute service endpoint or none of them can be
reached then the user will be redirected to the login page with
a message.

Closes-Bug: 1323811
Change-Id: I31c7d70f49f82b6a7fe663fe043ec279ad3c8119

commit_message:
Implement retry on NodeLocked exceptions

This adds the capability to retry node locking when a node is already
locked. Two conductor configuration variables are added to control this
behavior, which can be totally disabled by setting the value for the
node_locked_retry_attempts variable to zero.

A new unit test is added to check that the retry will work after first
getting a NodeLocked exception, then succeeding getting the lock on the
next lock attempt.

Change-Id: I60b099beea1bc3a954a5ab4699e623aaa71ba6c5
Blueprint: add-nodelocked-retry

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-05-02 20:49:47.000000000', 'message': "Fix a few bugs when running with -u

The default conf file locator needed to reference the file another level up.

The config file set/write did not work if more than one option was changed.
I'm not sure why but think it would be better to just read once, set the
options, and write at the end anyway.

If we are updating and a service is there but not mentioned in the conf file,
we change the conf to True so should also add the service to the available
services.

Change-Id: I261f4ba08083cb7ed60c0a5bdd48a4dc16f4c23d
"}, {'created': '2014-05-06 13:46:20.000000000', 'message': "Fix a few bugs when running with -u

The default conf file locator needed to reference the file another level up.

The config file set/write did not work if more than one option was changed.
I'm not sure why but think it would be better to just read once, set the
options, and write at the end anyway.

If we are updating and a service is there but not mentioned in the conf file,
we change the conf to True so should also add the service to the available
services.

Change-Id: I261f4ba08083cb7ed60c0a5bdd48a4dc16f4c23d

commit_message:
Fix a few bugs when running with -u

The default conf file locator needed to reference the file another level up.

The config file set/write did not work if more than one option was changed.
I'm not sure why but think it would be better to just read once, set the
options, and write at the end anyway.

If we are updating and a service is there but not mentioned in the conf file,
we change the conf to True so should also add the service to the available
services.

Change-Id: I261f4ba08083cb7ed60c0a5bdd48a4dc16f4c23d

commit_message:
Fix install_ceilometer and install_ceilometerclient

Other projects do a setup_develop in install_*. This standard is used by
grenade to do installations. Currently grenade uses install ceilometer
as part of the upgrade script, but this doesn't actually install the new
ceilometer.

Change-Id: I4e44bec6574e6a4fcfc252418bc267191aef28fb
Closes-Bug: #1347178

commit_message:
Read template's expected value orchest test Part-1

In tests under /tempest/api/orchestration/, resources gets
created based on parameters defined in template (yaml, json).
But while verification of output, expected values are hard coded
in tests. Expected values should be read from template only.

This patch adds the helper to load the values from template
(yaml, json) and apply the changes in
tempest/api/orchestration/test_volumes.py

This patch also rename the existing load_template() function
as it read the template and newly added function load the template
This rename the load_template() to read_template in
tempest/api/orchestration/base.py and corresponding calling files.

Partial-Bug: #1327919

Change-Id: Ie0817e20cb7bacdf33b16fb222a7ee9c91109fc8

commit_message:
Fixes bad performance when editing project members

The bug is caused by consecutive client calls when
fetching users' roles in a project.

The fix was to use the /v3/role_assignments endpoint.
Which retrieves all roles in a single client call
(dashboards/admin/projects/workflows.py:
UpdateProjectGroupsAction and UpdateProjectUsersAction).

The compatibility to the previous keystoneclient version
is maintained.

In a scenario with 1000 users with a role in a project
(using devstack), the time to render the Modify Users
page dropped from 45s to 2.5s

Change-Id: Ic72ebea0db226faf98c5e04d00d76dedd1fb01c1
Closes-bug: #1278920

commit_message:
Fixing data processing image registry

The Data Processing Image Registry was not adapted to use
expect the "previous" return value from glance.image_list_detailed.
This change allows the Image Registry to work correctly again.

Change-Id: I990962483197f54ee9436278463c4709b909297a
Closes-Bug:  #1347036

commit_message:
Revert "Add tests for wait_for_server_status"

This unit test class added several race conditions to the unit tests as well as
added a dependency on having a valid tempest config file. At this point instead
of trying to fix all of these issues I'm pushing a revert in the short term and 
long-term we can just fix things and re-push these tests.

This reverts commit ae7c9ac4aac20a2832fe1beeaac0a688c6accbd9.

Change-Id: If6026611f3938be0716ce95491a8ee60a53e8c12
Closes-Bug: #1347096

commit_message:
test_heatclient fix mocking with latest keystone

The tests break with latest (0.10.0) keystoneclient, so replace
the mocked domain with a MockAnything object

Change-Id: Icd460e554656e11ef8c4bcda62c1363b7eed8a68
Closes-Bug: #1347319

commit_message:
Add cinder volume driver support for Nimble Storage.

The set of changes introduces the cinder iSCSI volume driver support for
Nimble Storage. It implements the minimum set of features required by the
icehouse release. Please see the blueprint nimble-iscsi-volume-driver for
more information.

Change-Id: I48781fc890b8fefb33027da3db2b1ff56c5deed4
Implements: blueprint nimble-iscsi-volume-driver

commit_message:
Ensure routing key is specified in the address for a direct producer

This change is already merged in oslo-incubator.  Note that for
Ceilometer this is an Icehouse-specific patch since master has already
been updated to use the oslo.messaging library.

Original commit message body includes:

    Porting this fix from oslo.messaging.  This fixes the impl_qpid.py
    driver to allow it to work with the latest stable upstream QPID broker
    (version 0.28).  See the Apache Qpid Jira bug
    https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/QPID-5557

Change-Id: If71f78e50f8a9b3acfd1e9d02c8271f17c4ebee7
Related-Bug: #1300318
(cherry picked from commit 096106f72fad5975bd0cb8ffa3447931c8fee9f5)

commit_message:
Add ceilometer compute notifications ostf tests

Refactor all ceilometer ostf tests and add tests for
ceilometer compute notifications: memory, vcpus, disk.root.size,
disk.ephemeral.size

Closes-Bug: #1338490
Closes-Bug: #1339105
Partially implements: blueprint ceilometer-ostf-notification-tests

Change-Id: I295b78ae9548e0da18faa4978c5bba78c91f5585

commit_message:
Allow passing kwargs from managers to session

Resource managers may need to pass certain overrides down to the session
layer. The most common example would be to allow them to specify a
different interface to issue a request to than is common. It is possible
later that we may wish to expose this ability to users as well so that
they can choose in there own programs what interface, endpoint name etc
a particular request should be issued to.

Change-Id: I7ee0931d4ea78cf9f463b2f0b54457226c5bea8d

commit_message:
Use correct project/user for quotas

This fixes the compute manager to ensure the proper project_id/user_id
is used when making quota calls by converting most of the compute
manager code to use the new objects. This does not change the RPC
messages to the manager, yet.

commit_message:
Correctly reject request to add lists of hosts to an aggregate

Attempting to add or remove a list of hosts to an aggregate
results in an internal server error. This patch fixes the input
validation so such a request is correctly rejected and a 400
error returned.

Change-Id: I760db36d685cff20b01a72160b8b3fbb8a70b412
Closes-Bug: #1321653

commit_message:
Make Nova_admin_tenant_id_setter notify neutron-server.

Add notification to ensure that changes in Nova_admin_tenant_id_setter
 will result with neutron-server restarting. This is necessary, otherwise
 it is possible for neutron.conf DEFAULT/nova_admin_tenant_id to not be set
 which will result in odd looking auth failures and cause instances to fail
 booting

Change-Id: Idbb2fe9ce63985e4236e41a642ef1b783bec3753
Closes-bug: #1343009

commit_message:
Enhance versionutils.deprecated to work with classes

If object being decorated has 'func_code' attribute, it is considered
a function (and processed by vanilla versionutils.deprecated),
otherwise a new class is created which logs deprecated message when
class is instantiated. Also 'Juno' release is added to possible
deprecation milestones.

Closes-Bug: #1335800
Change-Id: I12e7ad00af3bac35138cc0f8c7d595a08e8eda03

commit_message:
Disable periodic tasks in ec2 tests

We shouldn't have any tests that rely on randomly running periodic
tasks, this results in racey tests.

Change-Id: Id537e18a5fbd4e40d31204d1b13ec9ce83ce7e78
Related-Bug: 1311778

commit_message:
Add OSTF to the 'migrate_vm_backed_with_ceph' test

Performing of OSTF checks was missed after
environment deployment is done and it should be added
to the test as described in the scenario.

Change-Id: Ie06f76b462bf236fd06998d0236f90cbff792afb
Closes-Bug: #1324567
(cherry picked from commit 2c19e7ed2755d69167bc94a6e95509e66b81e93f)

commit_message:
Move create snapshot to finally block

In case if create diagnostic snapshot failed,
we can not create env snapshot with devops.
To avoid this  - move create snapshot in finally block

Change-Id: I6826930d997006a51ca79b94314f7df3c06b2f66
Closes-Bug: #1325907
(cherry picked from commit c021106c9b61e34bc24ad464b42a6104ce66bb7a)

commit_message:
Move create snapshot to finally block

In case if create diagnostic snapshot failed,
we can not create env snapshot with devops.
To avoid this  - move create snapshot in finally block

Change-Id: I6826930d997006a51ca79b94314f7df3c06b2f66
Closes-Bug: #1325907
(cherry picked from commit c021106c9b61e34bc24ad464b42a6104ce66bb7a)

commit_message:
Sync time on nodes before checking Ceph health

System test 'ceph_ha' almost always fails while
checking ceph health due to clock skew. That's
why an additional time synchronization and restart
of Ceph service was added to the test.

Change-Id: Ic6397e878fdca747f33e47f05e846d25f061ce7b
Closes-bug: #1336233

commit_message:
agent/lbaas: fix HAproxy package relationship

This patch fix this case:
- manage_haproxy_package is set to false
- puppetlabs-haproxy is not running
- we still want Neutron LBaaS working on the node
- we don't want at all the package managed by Puppet

Only set the dependency if the package is defined in the catalog.

Closes-bug #1340999
Signed-off-by: Emilien Macchi <emilien.macchi@enovance.com>
Change-Id: Iee2211db8add4dfafba70706d69d1092339c6206

commit_message:
Removing references of out-of-date versions of OpenStack

Fixing typo in ch_networking-services.xml and updating commit message
Ignored glossary and bk-openstack-security-guide.xml
Removed Grizzly 'workaround' link from ch_compute.xml
Removed Grizzly reference from ch_database-access-control.xml
Removed Grizzly reference from ch_database-sccess-control.xml
Updated link to Icehouse release notes in ch_management-interfaces.xml
Rreworded the sentence to be descriptive ch_networking-services.xml
Updated Grizzly reference to Icehouse in ch_networking-services.xml
Restructured sentence in ch_networking-services.xml
Updated Havana to Icehouse concerning FWaaS in ch_networking-sevices.xml
Removed Grizzly ref & restructured sentence ch_state-of-networking.xml

Change-Id: Idb1416148e8c3182b057d7f010a455a5fb7e956c
Closes-Bug: #1343562

node, taking into account the Domain-0 (i.e. the hypervisor).

commit_message:
libvirt: Do not take into account VMs with id 0

Nova was issuing warnings in the logs about the discrepancy between the
number of VMs in a compute node and the number of instances in the DB.
This is caused because libvirt returns the total count of domains in a
node, taking into account the Domain-0 (i.e. the hypervisor).

Change-Id: I4eee2cbd3d58a98021625aab2d711490e99fc810
Closes-bug: 1252654
Closes-bug: 1280315

commit_message:
Track execution cause nodes and triggered nodes

In order to be able to provide how an atom was triggered and
to provide what path of causes were when a atom fails we need
to retain enough of this information ourselves internally while
running and expose that information via a simple runtime/engine
only interface.

Part of: blueprint exception-traceability

Change-Id: I33a970284317aed70bba7ae0256a613bfa79b1df

commit_message:
Differentiate returned failures and actual failures

There is a difference between a task or retry atom
returning a failure object (which we do not prevent)
and a task or retry atom raising an exception that
we capture in a failure object.

Change-Id: I85035d12b154724ad76ac68a30b318ca0b623614

commit_message:
Make action handlers extensible and more pluggable

In order to allow other types of handling of atoms decouple
the handlers of atoms in the current runtime and make it
possible that different handlers can be used to schedule
and complete atoms.

Part of blueprint plug-engine

Change-Id: Id97cde20e5630fc1e28f9dee87871c2d541d291a

commit_message:
NetApp iSCSI: move zapi client logic into modules

This patch moves the logic for constructing zapi requests into its own modules
in order to reduce coupling with driver logic, improve testability, and improve
readability. This patch also adds unit tests around the zapi request logic.

partially implements bp improve-netapp-drivers

Change-Id: I8983f7bc9c8e5262e5aa7138f6e85a258b2d1164

I know this is kind of late and the spec has been approved already. Feel free to dismiss this suggestion as being too late.

'state' and 'status' are confusingly similar. It's not clear from the names what the difference between the two is.

Looking at the implementation, it appears to mean the administrative and operational states of the service.

Cisco has long used the terminology "admin status" and "operational status" to better clarify the differences.

Would it be possible to use 'admin_status' and 'operational_status' (or something similar) instead?

Sorry for not suggesting this earlier.'}, {'account_id': 4573, 'date': '2014-06-19 23:44:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

commit_message:
Return status for compute node

Currently when return compute node information, there is no status returned.

When the corresponding service is disabled or down and users try to
do 'hypervisor-list' or 'hypervisor-show', they will have no idea of it.

Implements: blueprint return-status-for-hypervisor-node
Closes-Bug: #1285259

DocImpact

Change-Id: I17c53b454ccef023f298f1b8875daef965d2325d

commit_message:
POC - Scheduler client for ResourceTracker

This is a POC for seeing the level of changes necessary for moving
the ResourceTracker in Scheduler with an interface.

The main issue is how the RT is accessing Driver methods, as it
needs to backport all driver calls to the computeManager and pass
the values in the parameters.

There are still some open questions, see the changes with the FIXME
and NOTE comments.

Implements blueprint scheduler-lib

Change-Id: Idc989b407639b7ff441208b2138c103e8737f6a7

commit_message:
Update cinder install for RHEL, Fedora and CentOS to use targetcli.

RHEL 7, Fedora 21 and CentOS 7 now use targetcli (LIO) in place of tgtd.

Change-Id: I864c4c7bfd368f68d434e204df640c7b69e6bcad
closes-Bug: #1342812

Sorry, sahara and ironic are not incubated yet and thus do not get documented yet. This is something we will add when we come closer to the release of Juno...'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2014-05-05 17:43:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Are you sure? There are listed as official programs here: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Programs.

Barbican and Marconi are also listed.

All four projects are in italic and at the bottom of the list is the following note:

"Note: Projects in italic are currently (icehouse cycle) under incubation before inclusion in the 'Integrated' common release."'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2014-05-05 18:03:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Yes, they are still incubated. There needs to be a formal decision to move them out of incubation. Let's ask Anne as expert;)"}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2014-05-05 18:12:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Ah. So the projects need to be in state "integrated" before we add them to the documentation? At the moment all four projects are in state "incubated".'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2014-05-05 18:18:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Yes, projects need to be in integration in a release before they are integrated in the ops/user docs. For example, Marconi withdrew their integration request in the icehouse release, so we did the right thing by not including them yet in the docs. Project incubating now can be included in juno docs as long as they pass integration.'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2014-05-05 18:18:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Exactly, we only document "integrated" not "incubated".'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2014-05-05 18:20:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I'm pretty sure that Sahara and Trove will pass incubation during Juno cycle. Not sure about Barbican and Marconi. But I think Sahara and Trove can be included right now.

But it's also okay to delay this change until the end of incubation and official integration."}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2014-05-05 18:25:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Anne, is it safe to document any project already? Please keep the openstack-doc mailing list updated so that we can document early.'}, {'account_id': 6547, 'date': '2014-05-05 18:26:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Christian, Trove has integrated with Icehouse.'}, {'account_id': 167, 'date': '2014-05-05 18:36:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Sorry, meant Ironic.'}, {'account_id': 964, 'date': '2014-05-14 19:11:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Let's see. We now have a governance document at http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/governance/tree/reference/programs.yaml that I proposed so that we could have a lookup reference for when a particular program or project becomes part of a release. 

If we were to use that document for reference, Ironic would go with Havana docs. However, their release notes calls Icehouse a "stable beta" (https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Ironic/ReleaseNotes/Icehouse). So I don't want to spend our doc time on beta projects when other topics still need more work. Perhaps if the doc bug log was less than 100 I would consider it.

For Sahara, the project will be integrated with Juno, so I'd prefer this not merge until the release date for Juno, fall 2014.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-05-14 19:11:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

commit_message:
Add Sahara to the client listing

Sahara is missing in the table "OpenStack services and clients"
in the CLI reference (included from common) at the moment.

According to https://github.com/openstack/governance/blob/master/reference/programs.yaml
Sahara is an integrated project since Juno. Clients of integrated projects should be
listed.

Change-Id: I110be4b1840107bb6285dcb2738a5c76f97d29f1

commit_message:
Add CLI reference for Sahara

According to https://github.com/openstack/governance/blob/master/reference/programs.yaml
Sahara is an integrated project since Juno. Clients of integrated projects
should be available in the CLI reference.

Change-Id: I7196b78e8b5753464a55ddd7ff34b3a413f20f6d

commit_message:
Rename Host to Allowed Host

To avoid confusion between nova hosts and
database user host e.g. as used in a grant
statement we will rename that one to
'Allowed Host'

Updated launch dialog and users table to
use 'Allowed Host' consistently.
Updated launch dialog help text to clean
up some of the descriptions

Change-Id: Ice39cd6712eb757a4d0f5beaedcda580fbeb4acb
Closes-Bug: #1342134

_reclaim_queued_deletes will only find instances in SOFT_DELETED
state and delete them if they are only enough. The quotas will be
committed when the instance was soft-deleted so that resource can
be used right after the soft-delete operation.

There are some concern about the quota inconsistency for the operation,
The only case that the quota might be inconsistent is
the compute node died between set instance state to SOFT_DELETED
and quota commit to DB; when compute node start again
it will have no idea the reservation is committed or not or even
expired, since it's a rare case, so marked as todo.

There are some alternatives if the problem need to be fixed, e.g.
able to find reservation when nova compute restart, so we can double
check whether the quota is committed or not.

Partial-Bug: #1296414

commit_message:
Change the comments of SOFT_DELETED race condition

_reclaim_queued_deletes will only find instances in SOFT_DELETED
state and delete them if they are only old enough. The quotas will be
committed when the instance was soft-deleted so that resource can
be used right after the soft-delete operation.

There are some concern about the quota inconsistency for the operation,
The only case that the quota might be inconsistent is
the compute node died between set instance state to SOFT_DELETED
and quota commit to DB; when compute node start again
it will have no idea the reservation is committed or not or even
expired, since it's a rare case, so marked as todo.

There are some alternatives if the problem need to be fixed, e.g.
able to find reservation when nova compute restart, so we can double
check whether the quota is committed or not.

Partial-Bug: #1296414

Change-Id: Idf9c179b2dd439462a646568ffd5098cd5d7851f

commit_message:
AttributeError at attaching a non-existent volume

When user tries to attach a non-existent volume, AttributeError
exception is thrown in get_data function, where the right behavior
is returning [].

This patch is based in the solution proposed by Matthew D. Wood.

commit_message:
Copy-on-write cloning for RBD-backed disks

Currently RBD-backed ephemeral disks are created by downloading an image from
Glance to a local file, then uploading that file into RBD. Even if the file is
cached, uploading may take a long time, since 'rbd import' is synchronous and
slow. If the image is already stored in RBD by Glance, there's no need for any
local copies - it can be cloned to a new image for a new disk without copying
the data at all.

blueprint rbd-clone-image-handler
Change-Id: Ie71699e845e14251233efc993a690713f1118c31

[{'created': '2014-04-29 14:55:13.000000000', 'message': 'Adding cluster_template and cluster panels for Sahara

to define and launch a hadoop cluster (made from
nodegroup_templates).  They are in the same commit because
some of the functionality of cluster_templates requires
that the cluster panel also exist.
This code was originally from:
https://github.com/openstack/sahara-dashboard

commit_message:
Adding cluster_template and cluster panels for Sahara

The cluster_template and cluster panels give the ability
to define and launch a hadoop cluster (made from
nodegroup_templates).  They are in the same commit because
some of the functionality of cluster_templates requires
that the cluster panel also exist.
This code was originally from:
https://github.com/openstack/sahara-dashboard

Change-Id: I85534b0dd97ce5def5f3a447d68c6aa206964f0a
Partial-Implements: blueprint merge-sahara-dashboard
Co-Authored-By: Nikita Konovalov <nkonovalov@mirantis.com>
Co-Authored-By: Dmitry Mescheryakov <dmescheryakov@mirantis.com>

commit_message:
Format eph disk with  specified format in libvirt

novaclient has following command parameters:
--ephemeral size=<size>[,format=<format>]
Create and attach a local ephemeral block device of
<size> GB and format it to <format>.

so mkfs should use the specified format instead of using
default format.

Change-Id: I7a8753284d7b1da1a1203e85b430bd0c5012937a
Closes-Bug: #1280132

commit_message:
Refactored datastores to use common chown function

Refactored the mongdb and couchbase managers to use the common change_owner
function defined in trove/guestagent/common/operating_system.py instead
of rolling their own cmds to do the same thing.

Change-Id: Ia7cf3bacf32b50ebf857d5b43ed756e4b09596e9
Closes-bug: 1314803

commit_message:
Make default extension path relative to pybasedir

Change the default extension path in the sample config files as these
take precedence over the files values in common/cfg.py

Change-Id: I3c473fb9cd7e81341a1963a35834ef4c2fd69717
Closes-Bug: 1316195

commit_message:
Tolerate service catalog and endpoint connection errors

This is a fix for the issues encountered when a service is not
configured or a service endpoint is not reachable. This fix
will add tolerance for these errors so that an error message is
displayed but the dashboard page will still load, not an error page.
This makes it easier for the user to recover by allowing them to
go to a different page, select a different region, or logout. This
makes sense in many cases such as when a region only contains an
image service endpoint, or when a single endpoint is not reachable
for whatever reason.

It also adds permissions to the panels that require compute or
image services so that the dashboard will not display them if
the service is not configured.

To test these changes you will need to set up your keystone service
catalog so that not all services are available in all regions, or
some of the service endpoints are not reachable.

Change-Id: Ie04699d1fb1d4db13a7f4dcf1bdfd23bf21aab80
Closes-Bug: 1323811
Closes-Bug: 1207636

Hi Veera,

I haven't needed to remove a dependency before, I think I would try to do it the following way:

    git fetch origin
    git checkout <my_branch>
    git rebase --onto origin/master HEAD^

HEAD^ should place only your latest commit onto the current master branch. You can check by running "git log" and making sure Daniel's unmerged patch is no longer in the history. When you run "git review" after this, you should not get a warning that you're about to upload several patches.

If this doesn't work, feel free to pop up on #openstack-horizon and ask for help, maybe we can figure this out together with other people. I'm jpich on IRC.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-07 12:02:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10: -Verified

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-05-25 11:56:13.000000000', 'message': "Settings page ChangePassword page and their tests

Two new pages added: Settings page and ChangePassword page.
To test their functionality I wrote two tests:
1. test_user_settings_change
 * changes the system's language
 * changes the timezone
 * changes the number of items per page (page size)
2. test_password_change:
   changes the password, verifies it was indeed changed and
   resets to default password.

To allow the above I've made few changes in other pages:
* projectpage - added the go_to_settings_page method.
* pageobject - added Selenium's WebDriverWait support method
  in get_element to help locating webelemnts (in cases it
  takes them time to appear).
* pageobject - added the timout attribute, from horizon.conf,
  used in WebDriverWait, and probably more methods to come.

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Horizon/Testing/UI

Partially implements blueprint: selenium-integration-testing

Change-Id: I24e01cd13d4a63ffd82505e4fd9cc95ba887e882

commit_message:
Settings page ChangePassword page and their tests

Two new pages added: Settings page and ChangePassword page.
To test their functionality I wrote two tests:
1. test_user_settings_change
 * changes the system's language
 * changes the timezone
 * changes the number of items per page (page size)
2. test_password_change:
   changes the password, verifies it was indeed changed and
   resets to default password.

To allow the above I've made few changes in other places:
* projectpage - added the go_to_settings_page method.
* helpers - added Selenium's implicit wait for self.driver
  in order to use page_timeout for pages that don't load
  instantly.

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Horizon/Testing/UI

Partially implements blueprint: selenium-integration-testing

Change-Id: I24e01cd13d4a63ffd82505e4fd9cc95ba887e882

[{'created': '2014-07-07 11:21:43.000000000', 'message': "libvirt: remove flawed get_num_instances method impl

The get_num_instances method impl simply asks libvirt
how many running domains there are. This is flawed for
a number of reasons.

 - It doesn't filter out 'Domain-0' on Xen
 - It doesn't filter out guests that are not started
   by Nova

As a result the value is returns is inconsistent with
the number of instances shown by 'list_instances'.
This will cause the _sync_power_states method in the
compute manager to constantly try to re-sync the list
of instances.

Remove the flawed impl and just allow the base class
default impl to be used. This just does a len() call
over the return of 'list_instances'. Previously this
was quite a heavy API call, but with new enough libvirt
it can be completed in a single API call which should
be fine.

Blueprint: libvirt-domain-listing-speedup
Change-Id: I96242717afa5c928f1cfb5f307b71739f2147e69

commit_message:
libvirt: remove flawed get_num_instances method impl

The get_num_instances method impl simply asks libvirt
how many running domains there are. This is flawed for
a number of reasons.

 - It doesn't filter out 'Domain-0' on Xen
 - It doesn't count inactive instances

As a result the value is returns is inconsistent with
the number of instances shown by 'list_instances'.
This will cause the _sync_power_states method in the
compute manager to constantly try to re-sync the list
of instances.

Remove the flawed impl and just allow the base class
default impl to be used. This just does a len() call
over the return of 'list_instances'. Previously this
was quite a heavy API call, but with new enough libvirt
it can be completed in a single API call which should
be fine.

Blueprint: libvirt-domain-listing-speedup
Change-Id: I96242717afa5c928f1cfb5f307b71739f2147e69

commit_message:
Re-add H803 to flake8 ignore list.

I6c2537dd27c947e36ebf37eb3b5c8a1ab8b026a1 mistakenly removed H803 since
running flake8 had no hits for this test, but H803 is the period in the
commit message which we are explicitly ignoring until the next version
of hacking is released (which will remove this check).

Change-Id: I22860cc61336ef5bf8ce4509fe130160bdf7e45b

commit_message:
Add neutron support

- Add network driver to switch between nova-network (default) and neutron
- Add option to perform Security group management via neutron
- IP filter for instance detailed view (hiding trove owned/managed network info)
- Add unittests and intergration tests

Implements blueprint neutron-support

  Related patch:
    SHA:        bd54d99aa0b717007d79891eb7839b660616eb6f

Change-Id: Ia0103bcda6590a4e387038ec035aee15454cdf48

commit_message:
Comment out predefined admin_token from trove

Trove shipped Icehouse with a testing admin_token in its paste file.
This admin token is not going to be relevant to any other deployment and
means this token is tried on first authentication attempt.

Change-Id: I27293f6138d24159057e7a080d08065149f2826c

commit_message:
Add interprocess locks to net interfaces handlers

Manila uses one service network for all backends, in this case
handling of all shared net resources should be covered with locks
in network modules.

Changes:
- added decorator 'device_name_synchronized' to remove concurrency
  issues.
- changed arg positions in related methods to satisfy requirement of
  decorator.
- with change of arg position was removed arg 'network_id' in
  metaclass 'LinuxInterfaceDriver' as redundant.

Change-Id: I7468f0a85bbc2752cfd82ae85d7491636ddea24b
Closes-Bug: #1346796

commit_message:
Fix obtaining of service instance ip

On service instance creation step using service_instance module
we try obtain ip of instance by service network name.
This change adds one more possible way to obtain ip and
provides more detailed info in exceptional cases.

Change-Id: I472a17f02e1e208b3aa58d023b9eb72e936ffa98
Closes-Bug: #1292950

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-16 11:28:58.000000000', 'message': 'Refactor test framework

Manila's test framework is pretty old and requires update.

Changes:
- usage of nose replaced with testr
- now all the tests a thread safe
- added new options for run_tests.sh, such as --concurrency, --debug, etc...
- new '--concurrency' option for run_tests.sh defaults to 1, examples:
    ./run_tests.sh  # will run in 1 thread
    ./run_tests.sh --concurrency 2  # will run tests in 2 threads
- added tools/colorizer.py for colorizing output of testrun with run_tests.sh
- tests running with tox use as much threads as cores available by default
- Added 'Database' class to manila.test module, for more conveniant db testing
- updated policy file 'manila/tests/policy.json' to allow share-network actions
- removed nose-related requirements
- added new requirements for testrepository, subunit

With merge of this change all old installed virtual environments becomes
incompatible and should be removed with "rm -rf .tox .venv" before testrun.

Implements blueprint testr-with-unittests

Change-Id: I9579ecd538e29d478dbc12adc7dcc33fc668b397

commit_message:
Refactor test framework

Manila's test framework is pretty old and requires update.

Changes:
- usage of nose replaced with testr
- now all the tests are thread safe
- added new options for run_tests.sh, such as --concurrency, --debug, etc...
- new '--concurrency' option for run_tests.sh defaults to 1, examples:
    ./run_tests.sh  # will run in 1 thread
    ./run_tests.sh --concurrency 2  # will run tests in 2 threads
- added tools/colorizer.py for colorizing output of testrun with run_tests.sh
- tests running with tox use as much threads as cores available by default
- examples of testrun with tox:
    tox  # will run test suites defined with 'envlist' in tox.ini, now it is pep8,py26,py27
    tox -epy27  # amount of threads is equal to amount of cores
    tox -epy27 -- --concurrency=2  # amount of threads is 2
    tox -epy27 -- --concurrency=4  # amount of threads is 4
- Added 'Database' class to manila.test module, for more conveniant db testing
- updated policy file 'manila/tests/policy.json' to allow share-network actions
- removed nose-related requirements
- added new requirements for testrepository, subunit

With merge of this change all old installed virtual environments become
incompatible and should be removed with "rm -rf .tox .venv" before testrun.

Implements blueprint testr-with-unittests

Change-Id: I9579ecd538e29d478dbc12adc7dcc33fc668b397

commit_message:
Add explicit import of _ to hp_3par_fc and iscsi

Messages using translation were added to the hp_3par_fc and
hp_3par_iscsi files but an explicit import of gettextutils _ was not
included.

This fixes that problem.

Change-Id: I2555860c6525a00295e823ab8c826b2bec6a3098
Closes-Bug: 1347184

commit_message:
Replace UserManager with None in tests

Don't access keystoneclient's UserManager in tests. This should be
considered private data of keystoneclient and is not actually used by
horizon tests.

Change-Id: I261e79b31dfc7388adb3dc63a3a5e54042f05e54
Closes-Bug: #1347236

I hate to push this back, but I wonder if splitting on something as ubiquitous as a space is a good idea.

One option might be to use json.loads to convert a JSON style list- if it can't be converted, you know its just a string and can use all the old tricks Auston is talking about, otherwise it has to be a list.

So the packages string would look like:
"[\"package1\", \"package2\",... etc...]"

Which could become a list like this:
try:
    list = json.loads(package)
except JsonError: #*sic*, not sure this is the right exception type
    # same code as before'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-21 15:43:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: -Verified

@Craig I'm aware of that. Sorry, I probably wasn't clear: what I meant was the list of packages stored in the database should be a string that is parable as a JSON list. I'm referring to the Trove server-side code which sends the RPC message: it could see that the packages string was clearly a JSON list and thus *know* it's a list versus just a string with spaces in it.

The more I think about it, making it a JSON list seems gross. But I'm not sure what else we could do other than going hog-wild and actually making a list of packages in the database that get associated with each datastore version. commit_message:
guestagent contract for packages should be a list

the guestagent contract on the prepare call sends the packages to
install as a long space delimited string and this should be a list. The
other parameters are lists like users and databases. The packages should
be a list as well.

Closes-Bug: #1341966
Change-Id: I05233bfce6d4b81351b797a30d3a55313edf277e

commit_message:
Restrict backup-list on instance to tenant

Fixed backup-list on an instance, so that we show all available backups for
the instance iff the user making the request is an admin. For a non-admin
user, we return only the backups in his particular tenant.

Change-Id: I2aff6dca053d8261bb70083bf52dac46806faabe
Closes-bug: 1295325

I noticed one other oddity: the unlink happens after yield. If the caller tried to unlock the file, the unlink would only happen after the yield returned, on a file that's unlocked. Fortunately, our existing use pattern does not use unlink=True, so this problem does not arise. Still, do you think it would be worth to re-define how bult-in unlink works by moving it ahead of the yield?"}, {'account_id': 2828, 'date': '2014-07-21 15:32:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I don't think the caller would ever unlock the file.. it should probably just let the lock go away when the context manager closes the file descriptor.  If I understand what you're saying correctly.

For what I was trying to use it for, I'd be worried about losing data if the file's unlinked before the file object is yielded, and the calling code fails somehow while processing."}, {'account_id': 597, 'date': '2014-07-21 16:57:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 2622, 'date': '2014-07-22 22:38:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-22 22:38:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: -Verified

[{'created': '2014-07-21 08:50:23.000000000', 'message': "lock_file race fixes

I attempted to use this function and found a few problems.

We shouldn’t unlink the file after closing it, because someone else could lock
it in between.  Switch to unlink before close.

If someone else locked the file between our open and flock, they are likely to
unlink it out from underneath us.  Then we have a lock on a file that no longer
exists.  So stat the filename after locking to make sure the inode hasn't
changed or gone away.

We probably shouldn’t unlink the file if we time out waiting for a lock.  So
move that to before the finally block.

Change-Id: Id1858c97805d3ab81c584eaee8ce0d43d34a8089
"}]
commit_message:
lock_file race fixes

I attempted to use this function and found a few problems.

We shouldn’t unlink the file after closing it, because someone else could lock
it in between.  Switch to unlink before close.

If someone else locked the file between our open and flock, they are likely to
unlink it out from underneath us.  Then we have a lock on a file that no longer
exists.  So stat the filename after locking to make sure the inode hasn't
changed or gone away.

We probably shouldn’t unlink the file if we time out waiting for a lock.  So
move that to before the finally block.

Change-Id: Id1858c97805d3ab81c584eaee8ce0d43d34a8089

commit_message:
SeaMicro to use the new ManagementInterface

Add the new ManagementInterface to the SeaMicro driver promoting the
set_boot_device() method from the VendorPassthru to the new interface.

The test_set_boot_device_no_input() test was removed because now inputting
a device is part of the function declaration.

Implements: blueprint new-management-interface
Change-Id: I2c5d0bba9045ce27c6b81ddefb6ca6bb019f2991

commit_message:
Adds Hyper-V Compute Driver soft reboot implementation

Adds a soft reboot implementation for feature parity with other
Nova drivers as specified in the base virt driver's interface.

Co-Authored-By: Simona Iuliana Toader <itoader@cloudbasesolutions.com>

Implements: blueprint hyper-v-soft-reboot

[{'created': '2014-07-20 17:29:47.000000000', 'message': 'Correct use of nova.image.glance in compute API

The nova.api.openstack.compute.images modules was using the
nova.image.glance module directly, instead of using the new,
standardized nova.image.API module.

This patch corrects that usage and updates the associated unit tests to
use mock instead of the nova.tests.api.fake.stub_out_glance() method.

Copies the nova.tests.api.fake._make_image_fixtures() call to a new
nova.tests.image_fixtures module, and corrects a number of errors in the
original function, including not returning datetime objects for
timestamp fields (as the nova.image.API returns) and ensuring that the
ID field is a string in the returned fixture dicts.

The _make_image_fixtures() function and the stub_out_glance() function
will be removed in the next patch, which fixes up the image_metadata
module, which is the last unit test that uses them.

Change-Id: Icd22ff3f438b8ba476f2637c7d4129ea6d0f45e8
'}]
commit_message:
Correct use of nova.image.glance in compute API

The nova.api.openstack.compute.images modules was using the
nova.image.glance module directly, instead of using the new,
standardized nova.image.API module.

This patch corrects that usage and updates the associated unit tests to
use mock instead of the nova.tests.api.fake.stub_out_glance() method.

Copies the nova.tests.api.fake._make_image_fixtures() call to a new
nova.tests.image_fixtures module, and corrects a number of errors in the
original function, including not returning datetime objects for
timestamp fields (as the nova.image.API returns) and ensuring that the
ID field is a string in the returned fixture dicts.

The _make_image_fixtures() function and the stub_out_glance() function
will be removed in the next patch, which fixes up the image_metadata
module, which is the last unit test that uses them.

Change-Id: Icd22ff3f438b8ba476f2637c7d4129ea6d0f45e8

commit_message:
Manual install page needed swift info

The "manual install" developer doc located here:

http://docs.openstack.org/developer/trove/dev/manual_install.html

did not indicate that you need swift for backups.

I added the swift info.

Change-Id: I23e8565aee7e7036e4e6065e2c22f568e65ca7a7
Closes-Bug: #1342273

commit_message:
Use auth_token from keystonemiddleware

auth_token middleware in python-keystoneclient is deprecated and has
been moved to the keystonemiddleware repo.

so i ended up doing it like when you don't specify a version you get the configured default_response_version (which defaults to v1 for compatibility).

So more or less if you upgrade this code and don't change anything else you get the same old v1 responses - which don't work well for storage policies.  But if you're clients are awesome they can just specify /v2 and the new responses are right there with all their hawtness.

One problem with this approach is that it doesn't really do anything to deprecate the old api - which was sorta not great because:

1) the url didn't include a version, so you have to sorta guess at the clients intent to extend it.
2) the response data wasn't wrapped in dict, so you can't really make simple additive changes without a version bump

The new v2 api fixes both of these things - so it may be better to make that the default with an option to allow version-less requests to route into the v1 response format - which is disabled by default and only available for deployers stuck with clients relying on the crappy old format.  For new deployments you can still request /v1 responses, but you always have to specify a version?

Hrmm... that may be better actually.  Maybe new deployments don't want /v1 responses at all?  But, I guess I felt like historically we've been pretty keen on making things easier on deployers by supporting backwards compatibility by default - and I think this change does that - but maybe there's a better compromise?"}, {'account_id': 917, 'date': '2014-06-20 23:44:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Add v2 API to list endpoints middleware

The new API adds better support for storage policies and changes the
response from a list of backend urls to a dictionary with a key
"endpoints" that's a list of of the backend urls and a new key headers
that's a dictionary of headers to send along with the backend request.
In the v2 response format for object requests, there the headers key
includes "X-Backend-Storage-Policy-Index" which indicates the storage
policy index for the endpoints returned in the response.

Change-Id: I706a5b5be8002c633fe97b2429256735800a902e

commit_message:
Use immutable default values for args

Default mutable values (e.g. arg1=[], arg2={}) could have side effects
in Python. So using None as a default value is safer.

Added hacking checks for default mutable args.

Closes: bug #1327473

Change-Id: I7055e534b91df794550de6c3b243324e582d4430

[{'created': '2014-06-24 01:23:07.000000000', 'message': 'Improve --debug logging output

This change makes the following improvements to the output of a
ceilometer command with the --debug option set:

* Silences spurious logging from iso8601 and urllib3.connectionpool
* Removes the line number from the logging format, since the intent
  of --debug is to show the user what network requests are occuring.

commit_message:
Improve --debug logging output

This change makes the following improvements to the output of a
ceilometer command with the --debug option set:

* Silences spurious logging from iso8601 and urllib3.connectionpool
* Removes the line number from the logging format, since the intent
  of --debug is to show the user what network requests are occuring.

Change-Id: I1b286adf63b1ca05ec4fcfb27fbc939aa662cc7e
Closes-bug: #1324470

commit_message:
Ensure routing key is specified in the address for a direct producer

This change is already merged in oslo-incubator.  Note that this is
not a clean merge of the fix, as Trove's copy of rpc from
oslo-incubator is *VERY* far out of date.  However, the bug still
existed in the code.  The fix just looks slightly different.

Original commit message body includes:

    Porting this fix from oslo.messaging.  This fixes the impl_qpid.py
    driver to allow it to work with the latest stable upstream QPID broker
    (version 0.28).  See the Apache Qpid Jira bug
    https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/QPID-5557

Change-Id: If71f78e50f8a9b3acfd1e9d02c8271f17c4ebee7
Related-Bug: #1300318
(cherry picked from commit 117c18cbd9d5ab3970ad3775e156862f256a924a)

commit_message:
Calculate a suitable column width for positional arguments

Overwrite the method add_arguments in the class
OpenStackHelpFormatter to calculate a suitable columnt width
(max_help_position) for the positional arguments.

example output before this patch:

    alarm-threshold-create
                        Create a new alarm based on computed statistics.
    alarm-threshold-update
                        Update an existing alarm based on computed statistics.
    alarm-update        Update an existing alarm (Deprecated).

example output after this patch:

    alarm-threshold-create    Create a new alarm based on computed statistics.
    alarm-threshold-update    Update an existing alarm based on computed
                              statistics.
    alarm-update              Update an existing alarm (Deprecated).

Change-Id: I945e46bb9e0309b960e3322261d9d6ff9fa35b52
Closes-Bug: #1326471

commit_message:
Re-enable 'check_trust_roles'

Re-enable the 'check_trust_roles' method. This can be
merged after the patches for change id
I13ce159cbe9739d4bf5d321fc4bd069245f32734 are merged
(master and stable/icehouse for Keystone).

This changeset updates the new location for the check_trust_role
HTTP status validation (in services/identity/v3/json/identity_client.py).
Previously this was located in identity/admin/v3/test_trusts.py.

Commented code indicating the above location change occurred has been
removed.

Change-Id: If1b7f18d7a357f4b3a4b478e300a17f2cc4a6159
Closes-Bug: #1334368

commit_message:
Make sure cli CommandFailed prints out stdout and stderr

Having a CommandFailed exception without stdout is very confusing, lets
fix that.

subprocess.CalledProcessError doesn't print out stderr or stdout so use
our own error that does.

Change-Id: I3bf75d6f526bdc58e64bbc7d83911e9d63e4b801

commit_message:
NSX: remove unnecessary checks on network delete

Since commit b50e66f router interfaces are not deleted
automatically when the network hosting them is deleted.

The NSX plugin still has additional logic to ensure all the
corresponding backend resources have been deleted as well.
Such logic is now obsolete and can be removed. Moreover it
also wasteful as it perform queries for retrieving NSX
resource identifiers.

This patch also amends a few related log statement to make
them clearer.

Change-Id: If3d8d98096a8363b216707f2558e37c80f58e515
Closes-Bug: #1339401

commit_message:
Fix error status code for cloudpipe_update

When passing bad body in a request, most APIs return BadRequest response.
However, cloudpipe_update API doesn't do it.
This patch fixes the error status code and adds a unit test related to
this change.

Change-Id: I16a48e6913f52baa870e04196529fda619c03098

commit_message:
Fix unit tests related to cloudpipe_update

In some unit tests related to cloudpipe_update, there are two negative
factors(ex. bad url and bad body) and current tests don't verify its
purposes. This patch removes unnecessary factor.

Change-Id: I5e78b47e6f4c7359a7f0c16898a26e3649d92eb2

commit_message:
add get_by_metadata_key to AggregateList object

This change adds the get_by_metadata_key function to the AggregateList object
and the aggregate_get_by_metadata_key function to the DB API.

Previously, the only DB API function available for finding aggregates matching
a metadata key returned a dictionary of aggregated metadata. The
aggregate_get_by_metadata_key function returns all rows matching the specified
metadata key, and is called by the existing aggregate_host_get_by_metadata_key
DB API function.

The get_by_metadata_key function returns a list of Aggregate objects matching
the specified metadata key.

Related to blueprint compute-manager-objects-juno

Change-Id: If50c9f613dd192ab44577f26a81dd5b40e3a7af7

commit_message:
Use CMS to decode PKI tokens

Due to the need to pass PKI token ids (not the short IDs) to the backend
the cache layer no longer support toggling the use of key_manglers. Now
the AuthContext middleware and the PKI token provider should now decode
the PKI token data instead of reconstructing the tokens each time. The
only exception to the regeneration rule is if a V2 token is validated
against the V3 API and vice-versa due to the differences in token
data.

DocImpact

bp: ephemeral-pki-tokens
Change-Id: I88350e93d9b060f6100309a6e980ef00a4ef3928

commit_message:
Pre-save Fuel default settings in all cases

If you open fuelmenu and do not save at all, then
astute.yaml is not created and is empty. One
workaround is to always save a default config before
running fuelmenu.

Change-Id: Iea2521d08629c690ecece5e9a4f1aae34b8f5deb
Closes-Bug: #1314224

commit_message:
Explicitly name element enable-serial-console

We use an element remove-serial-console in image elements.
Renaming this element to match. Also renaming allows us to use
the serial console in devtest runs.
See - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/86272/

Change-Id: I8f1138f58d0046ccdeefa3decc45c36d95c6bf4b

commit_message:
Rename/update common/tftp.py to common/pxe_utils.py

The functions in the common/tftp.py are not related to TFTP, the
functions are PXE related and most of them are used to generate the
PXE configuration file. Moving it from tftp.py to pxe_utils.py will make
it less confusing and is also needed by the iPXE work since iPXE doesn't
generate any configuration file under the TFTP folder.

The dhcp_options_for_instance() method was updated to not receive the PXE
boot file image from the parameters and just get it from the configuration
because we were always using the value from the configuration anyway.

Implements: blueprint ipxe-boot
Change-Id: Icfbaa4d6cdb9cbe0c392bf3dbd50ad980c70560c

commit_message:
Remove unneeded calls in test_shelve to start instances

During running of tox the system can timeout on slower systems.  This
is due to rpc calls to other threads failing in testing.  This
particular case involved shelving calls to start instances.  However,
when we started using objects, these calls became unnecessary for these
unit tests.  Thus we are removing the calls which should remove
the traceback for slow systems.

Change-Id: I52f1e86815cc2cac8dc31865f00eef2d4ffeea59
Partial-Bug: 1311778

I am somewhat grossed out at us adding another munging layer for our templates outside of heat... but I lack a better idea.'}, {'account_id': 9453, 'date': '2014-07-22 15:56:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 22:

I wouldn't call this "outside heat". The 'munging' is happening within pyyaml as part of its (de)serialisation routines. Heat can't tell the difference between us manually pasting the same net_binds block 17 times and us writing it once and aliasing 16 times.

The alternative would be to repeat the same net_binds block in each case where we need to use a non-default set of binds; in my mind having the same lines repeated 17 times is uglier than using aliases, but it does have the benefit of being more directly readable.

'}, {'created': '2014-07-04 04:56:42.000000000', 'message': 'Define a public virtual IP

Prior to this change our heat templates define one virtual IP, which all the services are bound to.

We wish to be able to segregate these endpoints: some need to be accessible to "the public"; some are only intended to be accessed within the cloud; some are only for admin use. This change adds a second VIP which we can use for binding only the endpoints that are intended to be publicly accessible, leaving the older VIP to be used for intra-cloud control end points.

This patchset partially completes a spec which will one day live at
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/tripleo/+specs/tripleo-juno-virtual-public-ips but for now can bee seen in  Id9addc65f0d2ed519ce4b3edbd561ed660a2786e

commit_message:
Define and bind a public virtual IP

Prior to this change our heat templates define one virtual IP, which all
the services are bound to.

We wish to be able to segregate these endpoints: some need to be
accessible to "the public"; some are only intended to be accessed within
the cloud; some are only for admin use.

This change adds a second VIP which we can use for binding only the
endpoints that are intended to be publicly accessible, leaving the older
VIP to be used for internal end points.

Haproxy is told to also listen on that new VIP so that we can expose selected
services via the new VIP, and keepalived is in charge of assigning the VIP to
control plane nodes.

This change has a proposed split of services between control-only and
control+public interfaces. Assuming our yaml parsers (in merge.py and
Heat) understand YAML anchors/aliases, and assuming I've got the syntax
right, this should get expanded so that all the control+public services
get their config defined from the same block without needing to repeat
it for each service. (AFAICT both merge.py and heat use pyyaml, which
does support aliases/anchors)

The default is left at binding to only the controlplane interface, so
that new services added to this map will default to being internal-only

This patchset partially completes a spec which will one day live at
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/tripleo/+specs/tripleo-juno-virtual-public-ips

I don't understand what the proposed fix is."}, {'account_id': 2903, 'date': '2014-07-17 05:07:27.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Workflow-1

I am unsure how to answer your comments Brant, what would be a "clear and understandable startup" be?

Does it mean each instance that needs the *_api gets it's own instantiation? This seems like a big step backwards from what we have (we used to do this, it was a bit messy)

Does it mean we still use the decorator, just don't do the future_dependency stuff? This seems most reasonable. But still leans towards using the REGISTRY global-y-thing that you're against.'}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2014-07-22 14:06:35.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Morgan -

An application has 2 general phases, a startup/setup phase and running phase. This means that the code should be structured like:

 setup()
 run()

Keystone pretty much has this already, except we call it load_backends. And it takes advantage of the magic of the existing DI system to store instances or managers and pass them around.

There's no need for each instance to have its own instantiation since you can pass references to other objects.

Whether a decorator is used or not is an implementation detail, although I don't see the point of it since you can just pass in a reference to the objects that the new object needs.

Maybe I just didn't understand the current proposal, but for some reason it says that the base manager class is changing and I don't know why that would need to happen."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-22 14:06:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: -Verified

Starting check jobs.

commit_message:
Change Keystone dependency handling for manager objects

Specification to change the Keystone dependency injection to referencing
the Registry objects directly instead of setting properties via
decorators. The dependencies will be passed in on manager instantiation.

This is an overall simplification of the dependency system.

Change-Id: I771537ece72b07ac81f057cf2be1805df0a450b2

commit_message:
Make run_tests.sh a wrapper for tox

run_tests.sh is now a wrapper for tox instead of running testr
directly.

Change-Id: Ia16ff3a55ee8f7eeb2bdc2e156ff2266d7a2bf54
Closes-Bug: #1335362

commit_message:
Add ironic cli support for vendor-passthru

This commit adds support for calling vendor-passthru
methods for nodes and drivers.

Change-Id: I73dd6c74f4b069e297cbf2175ffbba39fc1d6df6
Closes-Bug: 1330777

commit_message:
Fixes test_exceptions.py for Python3

- XML is parsed as bytes
- The XML returned from to_string is decoded from a byte string to a
  text string for the comparison.
- Exception.message no longer exists in Python 3

bp python3

Change-Id: I3305433e52c0def422d9f04a4d9f04c6f017d10e

commit_message:
Reduces the amount of mocked imports for Python 3

The evolution of the code as well as the Python 3 fixes has made some of
the module mocking unnecessary.

bp python3

Change-Id: I57e535012d89ee307acd43724dd678263704596f

commit_message:
Disables LDAP unit tests

Until we have a version of the python-ldap library (or a
replacement) these tests will not pass.

bp python3

commit_message:
Add config file flag to javelin

Instead of playing around with environmental variables, since javelin
is a CLI, add a flag to set the config file path.

Change-Id: I1e82e0a8e72117ba55048b2dab7aa9a8ba00c1cb

Make javelin resources optional

The resources is configurable, so we shouldn't blow up if a section is empty

commit_message:
Initial Erasure Code Docs

This is just the start of some EC docs, the idea is not to add
more content to this patch but instead just to edit/agree on
what's here so far and get it merged to the feature branch so
we've got some living docs going that are reviewable in smaller
patches (as opposed to how we did Storage Policies).

Change-Id: I3d4ff2a5bbb8cad5d88fba4a116d7a4d3bad8c8c
Implements: blueprint swift-ec

commit_message:
Wipe each partition for all disks when removing nodes

If partitions are not wiped then old formatted filesystems
will show up if a parititon is created at the same point as
the previous one. This will cause ceph-deploy to fail when
bringing up an OSD. Ceph will see an XFS filesystem and the
correct partition GUID and auto-mount the partition prior to
activating the OSD.

Change-Id: I2b71ec429ac1982f3df585423ca0818b294d8210
Closes-bug: #1323343
(cherry picked from commit 9f1e69aa3a2fe7a6093fa50596d6931826d93a09)

So there's something else we should probably address this because it is so similar to L7 switching:

Right now, Listeners have a default pool, but there's no way at present to have RedirectToUrl or Reject as a default action.  To put this another way, right now the default action for a listener is hard-coded to RedirectToPool.

We can "fake" having RedirectToUrl or Reject as the default action by creating an L7Policy with an L7Rule that matches all requests, but that seems both clunkier and less intuitive to users.

I think we should address this concern in a more graceful way in this patch set. What do y'all think?'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-23 12:35:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Verified

Move to oslo.db

Replace common oslo code glance.openstack.common.db
by usage of oslo.db library and remove common code.

Attempt to force-delete a volume if the regular delete times out in the
hopes that forcing the delete will actually remove the volume rather
than leak it and cause other test runs to fail.

This is only changing the non-admin tests for now to see if it helps
with stability, but a longer term consideration should happen for

force-delete if they timeout, then we don't need this try/except logic

commit_message:
Fallback to force-delete of volumes if regular delete times out

Attempt to force-delete a volume if the regular delete times out in the
hopes that forcing the delete will actually remove the volume rather
than leak it and cause other test runs to fail.

This is only changing the non-admin tests for now to see if it helps
with stability, but a longer term consideration should happen for
refactoring the regular volume delete client calls with defaulting to
force-delete if they timeout, then we don't need this try/except logic
in every volume API test doing this same tear down.

Related-Bug: #1322011

Change-Id: Ia91e432608ac25f3472478c65f9f7700bbf589e0

commit_message:
WIP: Set size  for session connection pools

This adds a connection pool adapter in the non-ssl
case and sets pool_maxsize on the session.

The default pool size is 10, this increases it to 1000
to see if it helps with avoid cases where the connection
pool is full and new connections are discarded.

Change-Id: I8f2d89802ecbb03d79e804149424216a7e13a032
Closes-Bug: #1341777

commit_message:
Added support for NOS version 4.1.0, 5.0.0 and greater

NETCONF temaplates for NOS version greater than 4.1.0 are slightly
different (argh). An init time check of the NOS version is done
to enable selection of the correct NETCONF templates.

Change-Id: I01e82ad402fbbb25d92a99a3325ca2608dd514cb
Closes-bug: #1332719
(cherry picked from commit f807023246501b77e792371d98b612b208f5e8e3)

commit_message:
Remove docutils pin

This was added to work around bug 1091333.  A new sphinx has been
released and so this is no longer necessary.

Change-Id: I6ea61a3cc441dd1ca2ced7e2fd837a55b917f76d

(4 comments)

Both bugs have the same root cause: the consistent assumption throughout Nova code that shared storage always means that both instance path and ephemeral block storage is shared between compute nodes. This patch just as consistently replaces this assumption with the logic that differentiates between the two options.

In fact, if you go back to November 2013 when this patch was first posted on GitHub[0], you'll see that it was originally intended to only fix #1250751, the fact that it fixes #1314526 as well comes for free as a side effect :)

[0] https://github.com/angdraug/nova/commit/bdde23d7ae823d90c262c9e986a8f9ebe5c4f456

So I disagree about having to split this patch, the way it fixes live migration depends on the change that makes revert resize work.

I also don't think separating the DRY improvement makes sense: I would be removing the code duplication that only becomes a problem due to the changes I had to make in the first place.

I will try to replace SHARED_IMAGE_TYPES with Images property, and I have already updated the docstrings as requested (not submitting another patchset just for the latter so as not to burden the CI infrastructure unnecessarily)."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-05-06 20:06:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Verified+1

As you wish - as a general rule smaller patches are easier to review and get merged more quickly. I will review this patch in this form as well as it's important."}, {'account_id': 5511, 'date': '2014-05-07 15:26:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8: Code-Review-1

(7 comments)

I have reviewed this code some more and there are inline comments - some are errors I believe - some are just style nits and discussion.

But really I don't think I will +2 this patch in it's current form at all. It heavily refactors code paths that are 1) NOT tested in the gate 2) Cover too many options (block, shared, non-shared, volume backed purely but non-shared and this actually adds another one). Chances of not breaking some edge case here are very low.

My advice would be to split this into a series of bugfix patches that do no refactoring to make this possible to review, and then consider refactoring once we are happy nothing is broken. I've spent 2h looking at this and have 0 confidence I understand the full impact.

Although live-mig code as a whole now may be handling too many cases and needs to be rethought completely.

Either way - this patch is just too smart for it's own good in it's current form IMHO"}, {'account_id': 8787, 'date': '2014-05-07 18:56:46.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-05-07 18:57:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

(5 comments)

I still hope I can convince you to reconsider splitting this. Me and Ryan have spent a lot of time looking at this problem back in November and we did try to get away with a smaller fix, but found out that partial fixes only make it worse. Either rbd image is removed when it shouldn't be, or instance path is left behind and migration back to the source fails, or instance path isn't prepared it advance and migration fails, and so on.

Making gate tests a pre-requisite for any non-trivial commit is a slippery slope. There's always going to be more configurations and test cases than integration tests can cover, and the time it takes to run the gate jobs is already long enough to be a problem. You have to draw the line at some point and concede that for some cases unit tests have to be enough.

I agree that the current shape of this code makes it difficult to cover all live migration edge cases. If you have any plans or ideas on how to improve that please share, although I do hope that refactoring live migration unit tests can come as a separate code review :-)"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-05-07 20:01:02.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Verified+1

More or less agree with Dan's concerns, but there is also precedent here.  Just don't like to see propagation of a bad practice and we are just kicking the can down the road on when we could refactor the compute manager and virt driver code to push a lot of this logic from the compute manager into the virt driver for the live migration flow.

I am concerned about the RPC API changes that Dan points out in the virt driver about whether or not the changes are backwards compatible between hosts, if that's not true we can't do this probably, at least not without an UpgradeImpact or DocImpact tag for the release notes about live migration support."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-06-10 18:31:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 22: Code-Review-1

I am not sure that pushing this off until refactoring is what we want to do as I think this patch is just a bit more useful than it is "kicking the can down the road". Having said that - the dest_check_data should probably be objectified as it will break live upgrades (see inline for details).

From me -1 is only for that (good catch Dan!), I will +2 once that's fixed and I hope other's will as well - her's why: I've done this kind of refactoring once and it might be a bit too high of a bar for this fix - again - we should consider the usefulness/impact of the fix.'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-06-11 09:11:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 22:

'}, {'created': '2014-06-12 21:43:46.000000000', 'message': 'Improve shared storage checks for live migration

Due to an assumption that libvirt live migrations work only when both instance
path and disk data is shared between source and destination hosts (e.g. libvirt
instances directory is on NFS), instance disks are removed from shared storage
when instance path is not shared (e.g. Ceph RBD backend is enabled).

Distinguish cases that require shared instance drive and shared libvirt
instance directory. Reflect the fact that RBD backed instances have shared
instance drive (and no shared libvirt instance directory) in the relevant
conditionals. Disallow live migrations involving a compute host running an
older version of Nova.

Closes-bug: 1250751
Closes-bug: 1314526
Co-authored-by: Ryan Moe <rmoe@mirantis.com>
Co-authored-by: Yaguang Tang <yaguang.tang@canonical.com>
Signed-off-by: Dmitry Borodaenko <dborodaenko@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: I2755c59b4db736151000dae351fd776d3c15ca39

commit_message:
Improve shared storage checks for live migration

Due to an assumption that libvirt live migrations work only when both
instance path and disk data is shared between source and destination
hosts (e.g. libvirt instances directory is on NFS), instance disks are
removed from shared storage when instance path is not shared (e.g. Ceph
RBD backend is enabled).

Distinguish cases that require shared instance drive and shared libvirt
instance directory. Reflect the fact that RBD backed instances have
shared instance drive (and no shared libvirt instance directory) in the
relevant conditionals.

UpgradeImpact: Live migrations from or to a compute host running a
version of Nova pre-dating this commit are disabled in order to
eliminate possibility of data loss. Upgrade Nova on both the source and
the target node before attempting a live migration.

Closes-bug: 1250751
Closes-bug: 1314526
Co-authored-by: Ryan Moe <rmoe@mirantis.com>
Co-authored-by: Yaguang Tang <yaguang.tang@canonical.com>
Signed-off-by: Dmitry Borodaenko <dborodaenko@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: I2755c59b4db736151000dae351fd776d3c15ca39

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-06-24 19:09:13.000000000', 'message': "libvirt+lxc: Unmount guest FS from host on error

If an error occurs during `_create_domain`, we need to ensure that the guest's
FS is unmounted from the host in all cases.

This is necessary because, if we leave the FS mounted to the host, the
`lvremove` triggered by `delete` won't work because the filesystem will
'still be in use'.

The solution is to wrap the code in a `try/finally` to ensure the cleanup
routines (which unmount) are always called.

Change-Id: If863cf813dddc1e4554fb87b945c68b75b25f9a2
Closes-Bug: 1333827

Change-Id: If863cf813dddc1e4554fb87b945c68b75b25f9a2
Closes-Bug: 1333827

commit_message:
libvirt+lxc: Unmount guest FS from host on error

If an error occurs during `_create_domain`, we need to ensure that the guest's
FS is unmounted from the host in all cases.

This is necessary because, if we leave the FS mounted to the host, the
`lvremove` triggered by `delete` won't work because the filesystem will
'still be in use'.

The solution is to wrap the code in a `try/finally` to ensure the cleanup
routines (which unmount) are always called.

Change-Id: If863cf813dddc1e4554fb87b945c68b75b25f9a2
Closes-Bug: 1333827

Bump min required version for dnsmasq to 2.63

This patch bumps the min version requirement from 2.59 to 2.63
for dnsmasq which is needed to use multiple tags for dual stack IPv4/6.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Ib71b8a3a866f5781b57d1589741bcaae594b76db
Closes-bug: 1233339
