commit_message:
Move log alarms driver code to alarm tree

This change move the alarms related code of log driver to
the alarm storage subtree.

Partial implements blueprint dedicated-alarm-database

commit_message:
NSX: fix validation logic on network gateway connect

This patch adds validation for the segmentation ID when the
network type for the gateway connection is vlan.
This will avoid requests with invalid vlan IDs are sent to
the backend resulting in 500 error responses being
returned to API users.

To this aim this patch slightly alters the current validation
logic due to the fact that some checks are unnecessary since
the same routine sets default values which avoid the
conditions being checked.

Change-Id: If0e71f6fdf27a49f0eda727e21405cffbc260a7a
Closes-Bug: #1340431

@Pavlo But different project needs different version of hacking, other project may not need hacking version above 0.8.0. How do we deal with this situation?'}, {'account_id': 9542, 'date': '2014-07-21 11:12:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

@Ethan, that's the point of global requirements - if any two or more projects use a "third-party" lib, they must use the same version. Just think of dependency installation when OpenStack is installed from packets - what would be the installed version? OpenStack services are not run in a virtualenv so that one can install different lib version for different processes... And that is doubly true for DevStack where everything is on the same node.'}, {'account_id': 7404, 'date': '2014-07-22 02:16:08.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
improve expirer performance for sql backend

the model has been simplified which allows us to do bulk deletes
rather than looping through and deleting records individually.
this should improve performance significantly.

Change-Id: Ie99880438d7415d805a94d78df648082d5161417
Closes-Bug: #1289166

commit_message:
Use six.add_metaclass instead of __metaclass__

According to http://docs.openstack.org/developer/hacking/ it should
be preferred to use six.add_metaclass instead of __metaclass__.

Change-Id: I1775035ea998b78a52c28ffe71dda2ede1377b31

commit_message:
Configure write cache option of tgtd iscsi driver

Cinder LVMiSCSI driver is using default value of write-cache parameter
of tgtd iscsi driver. In this setting, write I/O from guest instance is
cached on dirty cache of a host.(write-back mode)

In this case, data lost may be occurred if the host crashes before
flushing dirty cache. This may cause a lot of instances to lose
their data.

In order to avoid this issue, it is better to turn off the write cache.
(write-through mode)

This patch adds "iscsi_write_cache" parameter to configure a behavior of
write cache. The default value is "iscsi_write_cache=on".(write-back mode)

Closes-Bug: 1336568
DocImpact

Change-Id: I7a495bc6118d4254576bdf1620a04ac537b3078d

[{'created': '2014-07-18 21:11:37.000000000', 'message': "Fix failure of source volume deletion in migrate_volume_completion

In VolumeManager.migrate_volume_completion(), when volume_status is not
'retyping', status_update is not set. However, status_update is always
referenced as dictionary on volume deletion path, so it fails to delete
migration source volume. This patch fixes the issue.

Change-Id: I06889dae326b9557e044f1712d9f3205bb68a953
Closes-Bug: 1344341
"}]
commit_message:
Fix failure of source volume deletion in migrate_volume_completion

In VolumeManager.migrate_volume_completion(), when volume_status is not
'retyping', status_update is not set. However, status_update is always
referenced as dictionary on volume deletion path, so it fails to delete
migration source volume. This patch fixes the issue.

Change-Id: I06889dae326b9557e044f1712d9f3205bb68a953
Closes-Bug: 1344341

Add new library oslo.i18n

Add the new library oslo.i18n so projects can start adopting it.

Change-Id: I65c44627dc1163d15962edef575134fb7c857a2e

commit_message:
Factor out deploy info from PXE driver

This factors the code to get the deploy kernel and ramdisk info out
of the PXE driver, as this can be shared between the PXE and agent
drivers.

Change-Id: I2c3722d091f02259aa9e6cabebaabf25eead8bc2
(cherry picked from commit 8368bf9c66eea3a5f4706c867e266e00a5886213)

commit_message:
Fix schema-to-template for empty schema

if schema is {}, the
schema_to_parameters_and_properties(schema)
function shouldn't get an error, and return
{}, {} for parameters and properties

Closes-Bug: #1341985

Change-Id: Ic206ba64811bf43080a9deebb7c3b4c19134c43d

commit_message:
Also run v2 functional tests with registry

Currently the v2 functional tests are run without the v2 registry enabled.

This means that bugs which are only seen when the v2 registry is enabled
may not be caught by the gate (eg #1308419, #1339775).

Here we enable some basic functional testing (eg image life cycle) with
the v2 registry enabled (in addition to the existing direct-to-database
mode). This should help prevent some types of bugs being introduced.

There is a plan to move some functional tests into tempest, at which
point these additional tests can be removed in favour of equivalent
tempest tests.

Change-Id: I774a277673390650874aad4334b28d1a872ea93f

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-16 12:18:04.000000000', 'message': 'XenAPI: Always add latest Cirros euc image

Some tests, such as test_minimum_basic_scenario, assume qcow and if
a qcow image does not exit, falls back to the euc image.
This change ensures these tests work in the stock XenServer environment.

Change-Id: I718f178f7e5e0fa4eebd17a49caf5254124092e3

commit_message:
XenAPI: Always add latest Cirros euc image

Some tests, such as test_minimum_basic_scenario, assume qcow and if
a qcow image does not exit, falls back to the euc image.
This change ensures these tests work in the stock XenServer environment.

Change-Id: I718f178f7e5e0fa4eebd17a49caf5254124092e3

commit_message:
clients make heat_url public

Make the heat_url helper function public, so it can be used inside resources
which require a heat endpoint URL, e.g to pass to an instance for signalling.

blueprint: native-waitcondition
Change-Id: If351066e9ad68d2e19dee955d5e9de87f527e17d

commit_message:
Use mock.assert_called_once_with()

One of the ilo unit tests makes a call to Mock.assert_once_called_with().
That doesn't exist. It should be Mock.assert_called_once_with().

Change-Id: I7b57483479ddcd5ae00122064f8d4a133e922ae7

commit_message:
Fix incorrect downgrade

In downgrade of migration b7a8863760e_rm_cisco_vlan_bindin is used
Integer type with parameter display_width. Integer should be used
without any parameters.

Closes-bug: #1346245

Change-Id: Ic444af81ed3ec25116d2171ab465ce473cba8113

commit_message:
XenAPI: Use GUEST_PASSWORD when installing DomU

We know what the GUEST_PASSWORD will be, so set it during DomU
installation; therefore if the installation fails for any reason
we have a correct GUEST_PASSWORD set rather than the obscure and
undocumented 'r00tme'

Change-Id: I684646a74f2cede43667a40556e247955e042ae4

2014-06-30 11:47:11.136 | Certificate is to be certified until Jun 30 11:47:11 2015 GMT (365 days)

commit_message:
Do a proper tls/ca cleanup in unstack

Certificates and the index were left in the data directory after
running unstack. That would break devstack on the next run.

partial blueprint devstack-https
Change-Id: I6eb552a76fb29addf4d02254c027e473d6805df1

commit_message:
Add additional explicit imports of _ where needed

It appears that I missed some of the needed explicit
imports of _.  I have now run through all the /bin/cinder-*
functions and ensured that they can be properly started.

This patch adds additional imports of _ and also changes
cinder-rtstool to use the 'cinder' domain as was suggested by
Duncan Thomas in the first review cycle.

Change-Id: I6477093cb817b5b9506dd3787f027e073c51f37d
Closes-Bug:  1345789

commit_message:
NSX: Optionally not enforce nat rule match length check

This patch adds the 'raise_on_len_mismatch' parameter to the
'delete_nat_rules_by_match' function. The plugin then leverages
this parameter for ensuring NAT rules deletion operations
are completed successfully even when duplicate rules are found
or no corresponding rules are found at all.

With this change, the 'remove_router_interface' operation will
correctly complete even in cases when NAT rules in Neutron and
the NSX backend are out of sync.

This patch also changes a check in delete_nat_rules_by_match in
order to make it less expensive.

Closes-Bug: 1328181

Change-Id: I856d67ef5ff6264374cb8f2569668da4c205ad9f

commit_message:
Add python-barbicanclient

Add python-barbicanclient, so that barbican can be
used by other openstack projects.  Specifically,
it is needed by nova and cinder for patches
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/104001/ and
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/104339/
to support cinder volume encryption using barbican
as the key manager.

Change-Id: I319f6cc834fb615f0a1c5aa22fabfbcff66ea771

commit_message:
Add a minimal gate_hook.sh script

This will ensure that, even after I0c44229b2f67c9ea50e3f8786dccd8c50eb8e5e3
lands, our DevStack gate job will continue to pass.

Change-Id: I63ec82bf5b6ee2c6b58608676ed6709adec6fab2

commit_message:
Move _convert_to_nsx_transport_zones into nsx_utils

This routine does not need to be in the plugin class. This patch
transforms it into an utility method and adds unit tests to
increase coverage.

Change-Id: Ieacc36e729c4db90efd33944f7cf05dcb30e1de9
Closes-Bug: 1340210

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-04-19 02:22:33.000000000', 'message': "Add APIv2 support to make host optional on evacuate.

In the event of an unrecoverable hardware failure, support needs to
relocate an instance to another compute so it can be rebuilt.

The changes involved in this patch are:
  [*] Add a new v2 extension to determine that the host argument
      on evacuate is now optional.(Extended_evacuate_find_host)
  [*] Doc regeneration.

DocImpact: The evacuate target host is now optional.
If 'host' field is not sent in the request, the scheduler will
determine the target host.
This will include nova client changes ( on the proper commit ) to support
this new optional parameter.

Implements: blueprint find-host-and-evacuate-instance

Change-Id: Ib34fb3120263b746ad2f8fe89c14137e36a07a53
Co-Authored-By: Juan M. Olle <juan.m.olle@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Andres Buraschi <andres.buraschi@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Anuj Mathur <anujm@thoughtworks.com>
Co-Authored-By: Navneet Kumar <navneetk@thoughtworks.com>
Co-Authored-By: Claxton Correya <claxton@gmail.com>

commit_message:
Add APIv2 support to make host optional on evacuate

In the event of an unrecoverable hardware failure, support needs to
relocate an instance to another compute so it can be rebuilt.

The changes involved in this patch are:
  [*] Add a new v2 extension to determine that the host argument
      on evacuate is now optional.(Extended_evacuate_find_host)
  [*] Doc regeneration.

DocImpact: The evacuate target host is now optional.
If 'host' field is not sent in the request, the scheduler will
determine the target host.
This will include nova client changes ( on the proper commit ) to support
this new optional parameter.

Implements: blueprint find-host-and-evacuate-instance

Change-Id: Ib34fb3120263b746ad2f8fe89c14137e36a07a53
Co-Authored-By: Juan M. Olle <juan.m.olle@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Andres Buraschi <andres.buraschi@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Anuj Mathur <anujm@thoughtworks.com>
Co-Authored-By: Navneet Kumar <navneetk@thoughtworks.com>
Co-Authored-By: Claxton Correya <claxton@gmail.com>

commit_message:
move running of setup scripts to shell provisioner

Puppet is really handy for initial configuration of the environment,
however it's actually really poor at running stack.sh because you
don't get any output as you go. This instead moves that to the
shell provisioning tool to make for a better interactive experience.

Change-Id: Ia00a68d7ebd58a5b0ab653e53fb4e479b408c2a2

commit_message:
add vagrant_package.sh for building local cache

this builds a local devstack base box 'after' you've done one
manager provision. This is a reasonable starting point for future
cloning, and speeds up the provisioning a ton.

Change-Id: I5c9a7975e600ef3a29351b8897110537d22f1b5f

commit_message:
Always specify box_name

After vagrant 1.4, the box_name is something that is now required
at all times. We use the trusty official image in vagrant cloud
if not otherwise specified.

commit_message:
Use oslo.db library

oslo.db library has been graduated from oslo-incubator,
so now we can use it instead of ironic.openstack.common.db.* code.

Co-Authored-By: Ghe Rivero <ghe.rivero@hp.com>

Implements: blueprint oslo.db

Change-Id: I250050a7dbd8735ba3af954223b54eabae793f59

Added Request Body in one case.

Use InfluxDbConfiguration from mon-influxdb.

commit_message:
no quota for allowed address pair

There is no quota for allowed address pair. User can create unlimited
allowed address pairs. I add quota for allowed address pairs.

Change-Id: I7fec291a4838fba96b6d400ad56dbcdba9584d0f
Closes-Bug: #1336207
(cherry picked from commit I2efb0c0f527f1fb22c4d4b07f6d280863f565648)

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

commit_message:
Remove stubs in favor of mock in test_policy

This patch converts tests_policy to use mock instead of stubs. I was
stealing some tests from nova to another openstack project and made this
change there so I figured nova would benefit from it too.

Change-Id: I6d086795c559ac8f04028d820e8e88bfd5305426

commit_message:
Create test images via Glance instead of Nova

When possible, create blank test images in Glance instead of relying on
snapshotting, which may not be supported on the hypervisors under test.

commit_message:
check-sanity skip checking q-fwaas and q-l3

FWaaS is running as a service plugin in neutron-server and doesn't have
any dedicated process. When Neutron is deployed with VPNaaS it's running
instead of l3-agent with the same capabilites as L3 agent has. Thus
checking whether processes for these services are running is not
necessary.

Change-Id: I8f438cfccc84be801d4064bdb564a95c6621bf55

commit_message:
XenAPI: Fix race condition on tailing stack.log

Stack.log is created by stack.sh, which is started by run.sh.  Using
the pid from run.sh doesn't mean that stack.log has been created yet
so wait for the log to be created before tailing

Change-Id: I86e563478949cb7bbe0d1afd80b790ba70328e3a

commit_message:
Add WSGISocketPrefix to apache keystone config

I think since probably fdf1cffbd5d2a7b47d5bdadbc0755fcb2ff6d52f
devstack on RHEL6 fails and it comes down to:

---
2014-07-17 05:05:49.235 | +++ openstack role create admin -f value -c id
2014-07-17 05:05:49.615 | ERROR: cliff.app Service Unavailable (HTTP 503)

[Thu Jul 17 15:05:46 2014] [error] [client 10.0.2.15]
  (13)Permission denied: mod_wsgi (pid=30125): Unable to connect to WSGI
   daemon process 'keystone-public' on
   '/etc/httpd/logs/wsgi.30098.0.1.sock' after multiple attempts.
---

The apache user doesn't have permissons to this directory.  Adding
WSGISocketPath to /var/run solves it

Change-Id: If4b74019b6bd389b576fc981154bb1b3aa471c9b

commit_message:
Fix various pom issues

Mark some jars as only used for tests so they don't go into
the shaded jar.

Standardize on the 2.9.2 version of kafka since that is what
monasca-common uses

Remove the extra declaration of the maven clean plugin that I
put in

Change-Id: I2df38b53ba3baed8558a62dfe7de74f305f8172a

commit_message:
Allow to specify storage policy when uploading objects

Client already supports -H/--header option when creating container
or uploading objects. This patch extends this option to support
Storage Policy.

e.g.,
    swift post con -H 'X-Storage-Policy:p1'
This creates one container 'con' with storage policy 'p1'.

    swift upload con obj -H 'X-Storage-Policy:p2'
This creates container 'con' with storage policy 'p2' and uploads
object 'obj' into it.

Also fixes segmented uploading to non-default storage policy container

When uploading large objects with segmentation to container with
non-default storage policy, there will be another 'xxx_segments'
container created, but with the default storage policy. This
results all the segments to be stored with the wrong policy.

This patch is for the Storage Policy feature, and also
compatible with old versions w/o Storage Policy support.

commit_message:
Update retrying to 1.2.2

Version 1.2.2 contains an important bug fix to not raise a RetryError
exception on failure when exceptions aren't being wrapped.

Change-Id: I5203bf833fd015e87245661262b91ff8d0badba5

Justin, I think you need to look more closely at what Tihomir is saying.  Horizon should not create restrictions on the services that don't exist on the services themselves.  I played briefly with glance and I was able to create a variety of properties that would fail the check you put in, including properties named '', 'p*', 'q!', and 'question?'.  I notice that the command line accepts upppercase proprties and converts them to lowercase, but I don't think that means we should call them an error here.  Is it possible to determine what the real validation is in glance?  If not, I'd 2nd the vote to remove this check from Horizon."}, {'account_id': 9647, 'date': '2014-02-17 17:16:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I tried to figure out which characters are actually invalid for the custom property keys in glance. The two I discovered that seem to actually cause problems are tilde (~) and forward slash (/), so I will update the validation to allow anything but those characters. I will then also need to add some URL encoding so that horizon doesn't choke when the key contains a URL reserved character. These changes will be included in patch set 6."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-02-17 17:16:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: No score

Thanks for the feedback Santiago. I am not familiar with ImagePropertyFilter. How would that be incorporated here?'}, {'account_id': 10247, 'date': '2014-06-26 19:39:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

You are welcome Justin. About the ImagePropertyFilter, it is one of the filters used by nova scheduler to filter the compute nodes based on the properties of the image selected as bootable source. This filter takes three specific properties from the image and compare them with the compute nodes properties. Those properties are: 'architecture', 'hypervisor_type', and 'vm_mode'. So let's say your image "Fedora" has a property hypervisor_type=QEMU, then the ImagePropertyFilter will make sure that when you launch a vm with that image, it lands on a compute node with a QEMU hypervisor.

Since these properties are hardcoded in nova (https://github.com/openstack/nova/blob/master/nova/scheduler/filters/image_props_filter.py#L41) I was thinking that we might be able to "hardcode" them in horizon too and avoid possible errors. Anyway, this should probably be implemented on a separate patch, it does not need to be included here'}, {'account_id': 9647, 'date': '2014-06-26 19:41:42.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 10.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-26 19:41:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Thanks for the patch Justin, it does look good. Would you please share why you included the concept of "reserved properties"? I'm asking because there is no such concept in glance and we are somehow altering the behavior of the api, for example, glance-list result might be different from the list displayed in horizon (assuming that we included a couple of keys in the config file). Moreover, the blueprint is about "add, update, and delete image custom properties" and it does not say anything about these "reserved properties" so we might want to update the blueprint explaining the idea behind such properties'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-30 19:54:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: -Verified

Starting check jobs.
http://status.openstack.org/zuul/'}, {'account_id': 9647, 'date': '2014-06-30 20:34:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 11:

Here is the reasoning behind the idea of allowing custom properties to be hidden from the table. Reserved is probably a bad word since they are just not displayed. Let's say I have a certain image custom property that is quite complex, and I have added a separate panel just so the user can edit various fields and construct this custom property. There is no way the user will want to edit this from the Image Custom Properties panel, and it appears on that panel as a nasty blob of hard to read information. For this reason I wanted to include some way for us to be able to hide this property from that panel. This is obviously a property specific to our product but if we have run into this scenario it makes sense that others building on horizon might as well. I can be convinced to drop this from the patch if others feel it's not a good fit."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-30 20:43:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add ability to manage image custom properties

This adds a new action on the admin images table for viewing the
image custom properties. From this new panel an admin can create,
delete, or update the custom properties. The new setting
IMAGE_RESERVED_CUSTOM_PROPERTIES can be used to specify any custom
properties that should not show up on this panel.

Change-Id: I10a6049e8cc6a06f31497e17a66d7031cd049c68
Implements: blueprint manage-image-custom-properties

Volume Type Extra Specs support

Add support for set/unset Extra Specs to volume type.

Implements: blueprint volume-type-extra-specs

commit_message:
Set defaults for amqp in glance-registry.conf

We should set these defaults in glance-registry.conf
(they are actually the same as in glance-api.conf) to be able to
use oslo.messaging notification.api (in glance-registry)

Which is actually essential for osprofiler

Change-Id: I7768556aef17bb95123423f7e0cea54ecc21258b

commit_message:
Fixes name generation for Heat stack

In https://review.openstack.org/105117 despite what commit message says only queue name was changed.
This change makes Heat stack name be set to that name with 'murano-' prefix and description
in HOT template telling what environment owns the stack

Change-Id: I4a398a265031d0428497c6f91dfed88c7003ad21

(3 comments)

Since radvd is a linux-specific daemon you need to create a neutron/agent/linux/ra.py module with a RAdvDaemon driver class similar to the Dnamasq class. You need to have an option in l3_agent.ini called ra_driver to load the class. It can default to neutron.agent.linux.ra.RAdvDaemon for linux, and None for non-linux.

The linux-specific functions that you currently have in l3_agent.py should go in neutron/agent/linux/ra.py but please don't clone the dhcp code. Instead you should create a common module (neutron/agent/linux/common.py) with code that dhcp and ra can share.

See also some comments inline."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-29 19:16:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Verified

After discussing with Robert I realized that the l3 agent is already linux-specific, and we currently don't have an alternative to radvd for RAs, so we don;t need a pluggable driver class (yet)."}, {'account_id': 6685, 'date': '2014-06-30 17:13:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

with the comments so far, will do the following:
  -- move process_ipv6_ra into a separate module linux/ra.py
  -- put the routines that handles the config files into linux/utils.py and make them generic enough so that they can be shared by both dhcp and l3 agents. change in dhcp.py can be made later to use them.
  -- changes to address other minor comments.'}, {'account_id': 6685, 'date': '2014-06-30 19:14:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I just found that there exists a module called linux/external_process.py that may be leveraged for radvd. There is an issue in it that has to do with how the pids file is managed. It's used for metadata proxy for now, and the pid file name is constructed as <router_uuid>.pid or <network_uuid>.pid. In order to use it for radvd as well,  it needs to be enhanced to support more than one external processes per router, and therefore pid file management needs to be enhanced. 

With this, the only file that needs to be managed by ra module is the radvd configuration file. 

Let me know how this sounds like."}, {'account_id': 6524, 'date': '2014-06-30 19:29:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Robert, external_process.py looks like a good module to use. If you use <subnet_uuid>.pid for the radvd processes then you should be able to use it as-is?'}, {'account_id': 6685, 'date': '2014-06-30 19:33:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

one instance of radvd is launched in the router namespace if it has ipv6 enabled.  So using subnet uuid doesn't seem to make sense"}, {'account_id': 6524, 'date': '2014-06-30 19:52:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

No, you're right, subnet uuid doesn't make sense, sorry.

The uuid is just a string passed to ProcessManager. You could pass <router_uuid + "-radvd"> for example.'}, {'account_id': 6685, 'date': '2014-06-30 20:19:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

yes, that's possible. But I think that I'd rather to keep what the parameter name says and add another argument, something like service name. this will also make it easier for debugging /testing, etc. Make sense?"}, {'account_id': 6524, 'date': '2014-06-30 21:17:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Support Router Advertisement Daemon (radvd) for IPv6

Launch radvd from inside l3 agent when any router port has an IPv6 address. If
slaac is used for IPv6 addresses, advertise the prefix associated with the port;
otherwise, advertise default route only.

Change-Id: Ib8b0b3e71f7af9afa769c41357c66f88f4326807
Implements: blueprint neutron-ipv6-radvd-ra
Co-Authored-By: Henry Gessau <gessau@cisco.com>

commit_message:
NSX: Remove unneed call to _ensure_default_security_group

This patch removes an unneeded call to _ensure_default_security_group
which does not need to be called in create_security_group_rule_bulk()
as one would need to call get_security_groups() to look up the uuid
of the default security group which be would created it for us, BOOM!

Change-Id: I628a94c7ea9553dcefa68fa956f25244f0abbb18
Closes-bug: 1340536

commit_message:
Allow listing of resources and nested resources

This allows the engine to optionally include resources from nested
stacks in a resource-list up to `depth` levels below.  This number is
limited by `max_nested_stack_depth`.

Implements: blueprint explode-nested-resources
Change-Id: I43a5af25e74c7bfb32260f1616d36b311e0f2631

commit_message:
Cleanup and gate on hacking E711 and E712 rule

Fix the offending instances of the rule
and removes it from the ignore list in tox.ini
so that we can gate on E711 and E712 rules.

Most violations were in DB queries. Replace as follows:
  False -> sqlalchemy.sql.false()
  None  -> sqlalchemy.sql.null()
  True  -> sqlalchemy.sql.true()

Change-Id: Id84aa04697d1b3c23dc03195113e296c6715379d

commit_message:
Only conditionally import working keyring

keyring is conditionally imported if available on your platform,
however not all versions of keyring actually work. Specifically
we have global-requirements of >=2.1,!=3.3, so we know those are
the only versions we believe work.

If you are on an older platform, using system installed
python-keyring, python-keystoneclient won't install a new version,
because it's optional, but then will use a terriblely old verison,
which explodes with dbus errors.

The fix is to be more explicit on import.

Change-Id: I040f7b2311d7d5a450b8b12642752ac519b206fa
Closes-Bug: #1242992

commit_message:
Do not show quota of removed volume types in Default Quotas panel

Fixes the issue where quota for removed volume types still show up
in Admin -> Defaults -> Default Quotas view.

Change-Id: I2a822ac08b8347a8d76e8de70deca0e34fafe6e3
Closes-Bug: #1266906
(cherry picked from commit a7b6d82fd170bc594ceff791eb10b900a61c9175)

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-18 10:15:58.000000000', 'message': 'Initialize MeteringAgent object correctly

Class MeteringAgent is inherited from MeteringPluginRpc and
Manager. Its constructor should call both parent constructors,
otherwise Manager and its parent PeriodicTasks constructors
are not called and attribute _periodic_last_run stays
uninitialized.

Closes bug 1332788

Change-Id: I00ef804b6ee6c73dec3e177202bb85311e3e2b10
'}, {'created': '2014-07-18 12:00:56.000000000', 'message': 'Initialize RpcProxy objects correctly

RpcProxy class is used as base in classes with multiple inheritance
(ex. MeteringAgent). To initialize objects of such classes correctly
every constructor should call its base constructor via super().__init__()

Closes bug 1332788

Change-Id: I00ef804b6ee6c73dec3e177202bb85311e3e2b10
'}]
commit_message:
Initialize RpcProxy objects correctly

RpcProxy class is used as base in classes with multiple inheritance
(ex. MeteringAgent). To initialize objects of such classes correctly
every constructor should call its base constructor via super().__init__()

Closes bug 1332788

commit_message:
Make use of ip route replace in ensure-bridge

Prepending a default route and then deleting the old default route
could be considered an anti-pattern, so replace the code with ip
route replace to change the default route.

Change-Id: I627984d397db7cc2b2db7592b36b142d1da2c7d0

commit_message:
Add --public to setup-endpoints.

This allows us the use of HTTP public only endpoints. Until we have
SSL always on, we'll need some way to test VLAN configurations where
the internal network is unreachable, and this supplies such a way.

Change-Id: I8e9ba4ac70f0010ec832bf5a6287bcc3500b030d

commit_message:
Prevent extra API call when hostname not available

Due to recent Trove "list" API call change, hostname/IP is now returned.
So if hostname is not present in object, it is not available at all and
an additional API call should be prevented.

Change-Id: I39f1847e8dd6a5d010cc5d02c3ca09b216e3f627
Closes-Bug: #1341696

commit_message:
Fix /etc/hosts SELinux file context

/etc/hosts is modified and ends up having the wrong SELinux file
context. Run restorecon to correct it.

Change-Id: I07da602db49b0f122a86a95b5dc5d294fc95ce5c
Closes-Bug: 1344417

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-06-11 01:12:17.000000000', 'message': 'WIP: SELinux file context updates

OpenStack components installed via source are placed under
/opt/stack/venvs. The files in this directory do not have
the proper SElinux file contexts. Primarily the executables
need to be relabeled with the correct file contexts.

This patch fixes this labeling issue and gets us closer to
running devtest with SELinux enabled for distributions that
supports it.

Remaining items that need to be address and will likely go
into follow-on patches.

1. nova key-pairs cannot write to /tmp
2. mysqld.sock access is still denied
3. nova-api cannot start due to file permissioning issues
   resulting in dac_override avc denials

Change-Id: Ibffa1b986b52a1dc28de8d3b8056eed92aae9ee7

OpenStack components installed via source are placed under
/opt/stack/venvs. The files in this directory do not have
the proper SElinux file contexts. Primarily the files in bin
and the files written by os-apply-config need to be relabeled
with the correct file contexts.

This patch fixes these labeling issues and gets us closer to
having an option to run devtest with SELinux enabled for
distributions that support it.

Change-Id: Ibffa1b986b52a1dc28de8d3b8056eed92aae9ee7
'}, {'created': '2014-07-10 01:33:47.000000000', 'message': 'Update SELinux file contexts

OpenStack components installed via source are placed under
/opt/stack/venvs. The files in this directory do not have
the proper SElinux file contexts. Primarily the files in bin
and the files written by os-apply-config need to be relabeled
with the correct file contexts.

This patch fixes these labeling issues and gets us closer to

commit_message:
Correct SELinux file contexts

OpenStack components installed via source are placed under
/opt/stack/venvs. The files under /opt/stack/venvs/<component>/bin
do not have the correct SElinux file contexts. This change
applies the same context as they would have received if they had
been installed by a rpm package under /usr/bin.

Closes-Bug: 1340499
Change-Id: Ibffa1b986b52a1dc28de8d3b8056eed92aae9ee7

commit_message:
Load SELinux policy during image builds

Loading the policy allows commands like setsebool and semanage to
work on the image that is being created.

This allows us to tweak the policy that is embedded in the image.

Change-Id: I03c9ff95436bc603d9f4c442a20538252ab67c17

commit_message:
Call update-rc.d on mysql install for Debian

The mysql element installs an init script into /etc/init.d, but
that by itself will not start the service on boot for Debian-like
systems, with the service having to be placed into runlevels, so
run update-rc.d on Debian-like systems.

Change-Id: I50da62692c2f267e78be4c9c19e86e1af1273912

commit_message:
Update method in host_plugin to find hypervisor by name or id

The on_end event for physical reservations was throwing an error as the
host_plugin was trying to find hypervisor/host by name using an ID.

Updated the method to lookup hypervisor from the hypervisor list using
either the name or id. Also updated other references in the code and the
tests.

Change-Id: I6d5a0fea5beeb2e62aad1954591f6e1ced1aceaf
Closes-Bug: 1333342

commit_message:
Fixes a Python3 syntax error

Python3 has a new way to raise an exception with an existing traceback.
In Python2 there was a special syntax, but that was removed in Python3.

bp python3

Change-Id: I6811f7f46693fc84d0c61116cdd4897b6c20a9fc

commit_message:
Extracting get group roles for project logic to drivers.

get_group_project_roles is now implemented in each driver.

SQL and LDAP backends will see significant improvements on
performance (less queries made to resolve the groups).

KVS backend now supports inheritance and runs correct unit
tests.

Co-Authored-By: Pablo Fernando Cargnelutti <pablo.fernando.cargnelutti@intel.com>
Change-Id: I7a0190cd4a3b1eb26a09ef6436ca5450cf837135
Closes-Bug: #1205506

Hi SHardy,

Here is an example.

-David

1.  Create a new domain called domain 3
curl -s -k -H 'X-Auth-Token: ADMIN' -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -d '{"domain": {"name": "domain3" }}' -XPOST http://localhost:35357/v3/domains

2.  Make sure the domain is created
curl -H "X-Auth-Token:ADMIN" http://localhost:35357/v3/domains | python -mjson.tool
{omitted}
        {
            "enabled": true,
            "id": "9dfa8841fea144848e42c83a477a59f8",
            "links": {
                "self": "http://localhost:5000/v3/domains/9dfa8841fea144848e42c83a477a59f8"
            },
            "name": "domain3"
        },
{omitted}

3.  Create a new project myproject5, and set project domain to domain3
curl -s -k -H 'X-Auth-Token: ADMIN' -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -d '{"project": {"name": "myproject5", "domain_name": "domain3", "domain_id":"9dfa8841fea144848e42c83a477a59f8"}}' -XPOST http://localhost:35357/v3/projects

4.  Make sure the project is created
curl -H "X-Auth-Token:ADMIN" http://localhost:35357/v3/projects | python -mjson.tool
{omitted}
        {
            "description": "",
            "domain_id": "9dfa8841fea144848e42c83a477a59f8",
            "domain_name": "domain3",
            "enabled": true,
            "id": "26dfae8c205a43f98482ca7807c5f16e",
            "links": {
                "self": "http://localhost:5000/v3/projects/26dfae8c205a43f98482ca7807c5f16e"
            },
            "name": "myproject5"
        },
{omitted}


5.  Create a new user newuser7, set default project to project5, set user domain to domain3
curl -s -k -H 'X-Auth-Token: ADMIN' -H 'Content-Type: application/json' -d '{"user": {"name": "newuser7", "default_project_id":"26dfae8c205a43f98482ca7807c5f16e","domain_name": "domain3","domain_id":"9dfa8841fea144848e42c83a477a59f8","password": "changeme","enabled": true}}' -XPOST http://localhost:35357/v3/users

6.  Make sure user is created
curl -H "X-Auth-Token:ADMIN" http://localhost:35357/v3/users | python -mjson.tool
{omitted}
        {
            "default_project_id": "26dfae8c205a43f98482ca7807c5f16e",
            "domain_id": "9dfa8841fea144848e42c83a477a59f8",
            "domain_name": "domain3",
            "enabled": true,
            "id": "5511d0b720dd418fa16edccc31f22547",
            "links": {
                "self": "http://localhost:5000/v3/users/5511d0b720dd418fa16edccc31f22547"
            },
            "name": "newuser7"
        },
{omitted}

7.  Make a note of the "Member" role id
curl -H "X-Auth-Token:ADMIN" http://localhost:35357/v3/roles | python -mjson.tool
{omitted}
        {
            "id": "02401bcb396e4b5ba80d6b75e8d50d9e",
            "links": {
                "self": "http://localhost:5000/v3/roles/02401bcb396e4b5ba80d6b75e8d50d9e"
            },
            "name": "Member"
        },
{omitted}

8.  Add newuser7 as a "Member" to myproject5
curl  -X PUT  -H 'X-Auth-Token: ADMIN' -H "Content-type: application/json" http://localhost:35357/v3/projects/26dfae8c205a43f98482ca7807c5f16e/users/5511d0b720dd418fa16edccc31f22547/roles/02401bcb396e4b5ba80d6b75e8d50d9e

Run heat stack-list command
python shell.py --os-username newuser7 --os-password changeme --os-auth-url http://localhost:35357/v3 --include-password --os-project-name myproject5 --os-project-domain-name domain3 --os-user-domain-name domain3 stack-list

commit_message:
Add keystone v3 auth support

This change enables the heat client to use the keystone v3 API (in
addition to v2).  This allows user domains and tenant/project domains to
be specified.  This is necessary because keystone v2 API is deprecated
as of Icehouse.

Change-Id: Id19c4e52b12b379746a36b1f9fb61eb2825c78f3

commit_message:
Remove all 2.7 filtering

ordereddict and importlib used to break when attempted to install
on python 2.7 - but this situation seems to have improved in
modern pip/setuptools. Remove the logic and support for this.

Change-Id: I49d9c9ee3108ad7ec9537f3fcec62e84d4de1680

commit_message:
Stop filtering out argparse

Back in the day, attempting to install argparse on python 2.7 would
result in failure, as the setup.py of argparse failed hard if it was
attempted. That seems to be fixed, and when we do filter it out of
the list now, we cause problems with python 2.6 and wheels (if we make
a wheel on 2.6 and it depends on argparse, the pbr code means that
argparse doesn't get added properly)

Remove the filtering so that our wheels can be universal.

Closes-bug: #1346357
Change-Id: I49d539ac6fb8ee75f8d32fdfbd20129b13d36499

commit_message:
Prevent Messaging to resend failed notifications

Infinite retrying to send notification may cause osprofiler to block, if
transport is not configured correctly. So the easiest way to avoid this sort
of blocks is to set retry=0 at notifier configuration.

Change-Id: I5a4b75905dc8d63b612e193805bae28616e425a7

commit_message:
Add support for images context semantic validation

This patch adds support for images context semantic validation, it's one
of the series patches for the bp:
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/rally/+spec/benchmark-context-semantic-validation.
It just lists images to check whether the image service is available.

Partially Implements: blueprint benchmark-context-semantic-validation

Change-Id: Iecd54dc96110e5ce592478601f3c601e4275768d

commit_message:
Propose: Add QoS capability to the IBM Storwize driver

Storwize storage can configure I/O throttling rate to enable to QoS. This
feature can be implemented for Storwize driver.

Related blueprint: cinder-storwize-driver-qos

Change-Id: I1323591bfa0ca25ede5dc7c376bad4eeca572f1e

commit_message:
Fix rst formatting and fix tox

This patch does 2 things:
1) it fixes the broken formatting of all of the rst files, so they
   render correctly through sphinx
2) Fix tox so that it runs cleanly against the corrected rst files.

Change-Id: I3b3689c61054f051075dc6bc519c02e4c63626f7

commit_message:
Add integration tests (actions with workbooks)

This commit is first in the series of commits implementing
appropriate blueprint (please, look at link below).
In this commit I added a bunch of integration tests which check
work with workbooks(creation, updating, addition of definition and so on)
and use only python-mistralclient methods.

commit_message:
Deploy cloud hypervisor type

Proposes a method for varying the hypervisor type used by Nova in the
deploy cloud to deploy overcloud services from baremetal/ironic to any
other hypervisor type supported by Nova. In particular, containers and
Docker make this deployment attractive due to their lightweight nature.

Change-Id: I7d153b0341e148274590d3d049cf0e2141369e58

commit_message:
Add set_discovery_enabled to ManagementInterface

New method will tell the driver to set up the enviroment
for hardware discovery.

Add the default implementations, raising NotImplementedError.

Change-Id: I4549a7b4f217df5fb2e6be9d5b379aa79fa7e947
Implements: blueprint generic-hardware-discovery

commit_message:
Consolidate `assert_XXX_enabled` type calls to managers

There are multiple implementations of the various assert_XXX_enabled
methods. These have been consolidated to rely on the appropriate
manager objects (e.g. domain uses assignment_api, user now uses
identity_api).

``keystone.token.core.validate_auth_info`` has been deprecated
with no plans to be superseded as the new ``assert_XXXX_enabled``
methods now cover the functionality.

This is another step in the process to deprecate the functionality
from the token_api (and move relevant logic either the
token provider or other relevant locations).

Change-Id: I450daaca946e9695ff30e058adecef6ef0b9058a
bp: non-persistent-tokens

[{'created': '2014-07-21 09:46:35.000000000', 'message': 'Mark nodes to error if update was failed

We have to mark all nodes to error explicitly in case of failed cluster
updating. Such behaviour was implemented for regular deploy process

commit_message:
Mark nodes to error if update was failed

We have to mark all nodes to error explicitly in case of failed cluster
updating. Such behaviour was implemented for regular deploy process
but was mistakenly omitted for the update process.

Please keep in mind, that all nodes are marked as error only in case
Astute didn't sent per-node status information.

Change-Id: I945c96d8fc7a27cb7779894a1f69baaafd096689
Closes-Bug: #1332494

commit_message:
for OVS agent, fix dependency on service

Previously, the declaration for vs_bridge required the service, but if
the service is not enabled it's not declared.  This moves the dependency
inside an if.  See bug #1298146 for the background.

Change-Id: Ic51efb16d4ba0a971178ff648f963c61b2e9fdde
Closes-Bug: #1337733

commit_message:
Change of get_events and get_traits method in MongoDB and Hbase

This redesigns get_events method to generator style, with some additional
changes in unit tests and api.v2
get_traits method is also improved in this patch, additional sorting was
removed from get_traits method.

Closes-bug: #1339626
Change-Id: Ie65cc6f6c85eab53847176273b27de693bd2052f

commit_message:
Cinder .start/.end event notifications

This proposal adds .start and .end event notifications for volume
actions using Oslo messaging. All volume actions such as create,
delete, clone, extend, etc... will emit events to the
notification queue.

blueprint start-end-notifications

Change-Id: I55ca10071e10901a1a40a3f1d123fe3c9966a88c

Hi Sam,

Thanks for proposing this, but the code in python-keystoneclient's middleware repository is considered frozen (security maintenance only and deprecated). You can see the details of this in the spec used for splitting out the keystonemiddleware: https://github.com/openstack/keystone-specs/blob/master/specs/keystonemiddleware/audit-middleware.rst

All future development will be based on keystonemiddleware (and all projects are in process of being converted over). The keystonemiddleware.auth_token package will remain compatible with previous release of OpenStack and therefore can be used by deployments on older releases of OpenStack (the same way we endeavor to keep the python-keystoneclient library compatible).

If you think this really is a required change, I am 100% open to discussing this and considering it for inclusion in keystoneclient, provided we have solid justification.

Thanks and feel free to hit me up here (in comments) or IRC if you want to discuss this change further."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-18 20:16:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified+1

commit_message:
Prefer identity api V3 over v2 in auth_token

This reverses the default order of preference between v2 and v3 to use
v3 by default if both are available.

This is basically making the same change as the recent merge in the
middleware package. As the openstack services are still using this
keystone client middleware, making the corresponding change may need.

Change-Id: I010fb243a5403940127d391c3e3864cdb88aac07

commit_message:
Enable X-Auth-Project flag in HTTP headers

This also enables adding all_projects=true as part of the query string

This will set the "all_tenants" flag in the context, and does a policy
check to ensure the all_tenants is authorised

Closes-Bug: 1319112
Change-Id: Ic8c9a65a61784e0e08fa48961b7d6154d05fb11c

commit_message:
Allow form to stay modal after uploading file

Use JQuery Form Plugin for this purpose (placed in
horizon/static/horizon/lib/jquery). Browsers without XHR file upload
support (most importantly, IE<10) do not support setting custom AJAX
request headers, so form with File Upload field still loses modality
in them.

Change-Id: I163d20eac6a066551fa8ba7496bcc80aa59bf7a5
Closes-Bug: #1158501

Typo in the commit message.

I'm also not crazy about relying on a configurable Heat parameter to avoid port conflicts.  What happens if someone is trying to maximize their ephemeral port range and extends it to 65535 or something (based on my googling that's not unreasonable)?

Maybe there's no better way to do this right now, but I want to at least give some thought to it since this doesn't really solve the "someone else setting the port range" problem.'}, {'account_id': 7471, 'date': '2014-06-12 23:16:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

(2 comments)

If you can think of a better way to do this, please tell :).

If we hold heat metadata as the ultimate source of configuration data, then this is not an unreasonable way of approaching this. 

If they are maxing out their port range, then they will notice something is wrong when the image is deployed, and an expected service doesn't startup.

I think we need to provide a way for users to make adjustments if they decide to expand the ephemeral port range or something else. I think we have given them a way through the metadata and communicated what else may need to change."}, {'account_id': 7471, 'date': '2014-06-12 23:16:45.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-12 23:16:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
Move rabbitmq-server cluster port

The Fedora rabbitmq-server package requires an ephemeral port to be
used. Otherwise the service will fail to start if selinux is in enforcing
mode.

https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=1032595

This patch moves the cluster port from 5535 to 61000. Port 61000 is
also reserved through sysctl by setting it as the value for
ip_local_reserved_ports.

commit_message:
Upgrades, try to backup database every script run

We have a problem when user has failed upgrade
and during some time he can run the same upgrade
again, in this case user will have outdated db data

In the patch we create database dump with postfix
N in the name, where N is integer which is unique
for the directory and which we increment each
script run.

Don't fail upgrade script if it was not able
to make database dump and there is database
dump in the directory.

Also we keep only 3 latest dumps.

Change-Id: I9d7eab3a79690e4b4720bc7fc2548b83368e415a
Closes-bug: #1342112

commit_message:
Fix heat ostf-test 'test_autoscaling'

-Autoscaling templates were updated
-Verification that second instance is loaded was changed
(before we counted common number of instances with F17 image and waited until
this number increase, but that's not correct, that's why now we count instances which
belong to test stack and wait for scale-up)

Change-Id: I6c7cecf2f38cb73ef05c6eaea2c958e0cebded5b
Closes-Bug: #1334346

Hi,

Could I please get some comments in response to my comments for version 3?
I would actually like to revert to version 5 as the final solution. I know Akihiro had a couple of reservations about this but both points unfortunately aren't fixed in any other way. 
1. We need the change to test/settings.py to enable 'profile_support' always. This is the only way the tests can run with a 'profile_id' which gets initialized based on this setting BEFORE any UT is run.
2. The issue about my having written new tests which essentially perform the same function as existing network and instance UT but now with profiles causing two locations for code maintenance. As you can see I tried in version 7 to avoid duplication of tests. However, this seems to only work with the admin/networks tests/ In project/networks and project/instances, the override_settings I used similarly to invoke the existing test but to have it run without profiles causes a test failure in that it doesn't like the definition of the 'profile_list' mox call for when the test is run without profiles. [{'created': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'message': 'Run router dashboard unit tests by default

Currently the "router" dashboard does not have its unit tests
run by default. This was beacuse the dashboard needed to be
turned on for these tests to be run and turning on this dashboard
was not mandatory.

However, now that the dashboards are pluggable, turning on the
router dashboard tests, and more specifically the Cisco N1K profile
tests is doable and necessary. This fix aims to remove the checks
put in place to run the tests only when the dashboard is available
and instead now run all the tests mandatorily

Change-Id: I3c77a71db08ac611e5bdf9274af5a558bfda3327
Cloases-bug: #1229819

commit_message:
Run router dashboard unit tests by default

Currently the "router" dashboard does not have its unit tests
run by default. This was beacuse the dashboard needed to be
turned on for these tests to be run and turning on this dashboard
was not mandatory.

However, now that the dashboards are pluggable, turning on the
router dashboard tests, and more specifically the Cisco N1K profile
tests is doable and necessary. This fix aims to remove the checks
put in place to run the tests only when the dashboard is available
and instead now run all the tests mandatorily

Closes-bug: #1229819

Change-Id: I3c77a71db08ac611e5bdf9274af5a558bfda3327

Update RHEL 6.5 Image name.

The default value points to old image name

value to point to correct name.

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-09 19:56:35.000000000', 'message': 'Raise NotImplementedError instead of NotImplemented

NotImplementedError is the name of the exception
(https://docs.python.org/2/library/exceptions.html).

NotImplemented is the name of a constant
(https://docs.python.org/2/library/constants.html).

It makes no sense to raise a constant. The exception should
be raised instead.

commit_message:
Raise NotImplementedError instead of NotImplemented

NotImplementedError is the name of the exception
(https://docs.python.org/2/library/exceptions.html).

NotImplemented is the name of a constant
(https://docs.python.org/2/library/constants.html).

It makes no sense to raise a constant. The exception should
be raised instead.

Change-Id: I47efa6db2484757022d5f0601719d4ea4c78417d
Closes-Bug: #1339855
